<HEADLINE> PC Makers Flocking to Asia-Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Computer companies are turning
to the populous Asia-Pacific region to find new fortunes, after
conquering the West.
</P>
<P>
"The market is exploding -- no doubt about that," said Steve
Haslett, a director of Palo Alto, Calif.-based Hewlett-Packard
Co.'s Far East operation. Hewlett-Packard business is about to
double what it was last year, according to Alto.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Asia-Pacific was the fastest-growing PC market in the
world, with overall sales growth in the mid-30 percent range,
analysts say. Other regions, including the U.S., offer higher
volume but slower growth -- in the mid-teens or single digits.
</P>
<P>
Because of its size, China is considered by many computer
makers as the most potential market. Dennis Philbin, an analyst
from the International Data Corp. (IDC), said that the huge land
and its 1.2 billion people could take years to fully tap.
</P>
<P>
IDC predicts China will spend nearly 35 billion U.S. dollars
annually on information technology by 2001. In 1996, it spent
slightly more than 10 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Today, IDC estimates there is one computer per 200 people in
China, compared with one computer per 3.5 people in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"Even if you get to 100 people per PC, you still have a massive
market relative to other countries of the world," said Phil Kelly,
president of Dell's Asia-Pacific group.
</P>
<P>
Computer makers tend to separate Japan from the rest of the
Asia-Pacific market because of that nation's unique PC market.
Japan's spending on computers, though greater than other Asian
countries combined, is largely based on products made at home.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of Korea and Australia are also sophisticated
markets. People are taking home machines no less than a Pentium
running at 166 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
Asia-Pacific's market leader is Compaq Computer Corp. Samsung
Group of ROK is second, followed by International Business
Machines Corp. of the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. took the lead in the world in information technology
spending. It spent 41.5 percent of the world's total of 610
billion U.S. dollars in 1996. Japan came as the second, spending
15.9 percent. The rest of Asian-Pacific countries and regions
spent only 7.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
