<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Leaves for Washington Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto left Washington today for talks with U.S. President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are expected to focus their talks on security
issues, including the American military presence in Okinawa, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto faces domestic pressure to reduce the U.S. military
presence on the southwestern island, for residents there are
unhappy about the existence of a large number of American troops.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa is host of about two-thirds of the 47,000 U.S. troops
stationed in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Another topic likely to be discussed at the summit is trade
imbalance between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
After his three-day stay in Washington, Hashimoto will leave
for Australia and New Zealand. He is scheduled to return home on
May 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
