<HEADLINE> S.Africa Acknowledged by Zaireans as Honest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has been
acknowledged as a non-partisan facilitator and honest peace broker by
the fact that both the Zairean warring parties chose the country as a
venue for the peace talks, Foreign Affairs Minister Alfred Nzo said
today.
</P>
<P>
Nzo made the remarks in the Natinonal Assembly when introducing a
debate on his budget vote, apparently referring to South Africa's
mediation efforts in seeking a lasting solution to the ongoing Zairean
civil war.
</P>
<P>
It was also a tribute to President Nelson Mandela, said Nzo.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has hosted several round talks between the
representatives of Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko and rebel leader
Laurent Kabila in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is also the proposed venue for the first face-to-face
talks between Mobutu and Kabila, scheduled to be held this week.
</P>
<P>
Following talks with Kabila and consultations with Mobutu's special
envoy Honore Ngbanda last week, Mandela extended a formal invitation
to Mobutu to meet Kabila in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, South Africa has not yet received an official reply from
Mobutu to Mandela's invitation, indicating whether or not the proposed
direct talks will go ahead as planned.
</P>
<P>
Ngbanda, who arrived in South Africa on Wednesday and had reportedly
met Deputy President Thabo Mbeki on Wednesday night, is widely
expected to be the man carrying Mobutu's reply to Mandela's
invitation.
</P>
<P>
Up to date, there is no official confirmation about what message
Ngbanda carried from Mobutu to South African mediators. enditem

