<HEADLINE> Villenueve Criticises Grand Prix Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 24 (Xinhua) -- World Championship leader Jacques
Villeneuve and Ferrari driver Eddie Irvine severely criticised
proposed Grand Prix 1998 rules changes in Imola, Italy on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The International de l'Automobile (FIA) has ruled that the cars
must use grooved tyres to slow them down next year. Villeneuve
tested the tyres last week and described the results Thursday as a
joke.
</P>
<P>
"It was like driving a (junior) Formula Ford car, with a bit
more power and downforce. It's ridiculous to drive the pinnacle
of race cars like that," he said.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that if the rule was invoked, he and other drivers
might move to the rival U.S. CART World Series. Formula One
authorities encouraged the Williams team to hire Villeneuve after
he won the CART Championship and the Indy 500 in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
