<HEADLINE> Belarussian President Visits Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko held talks here today with Vietnamese leaders on
seeking ways of boosting bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Following a red carpet welcome ceremony, Lukashenko, who
arrived today for a four-day visit, held talks with his Vietnamese
counterpart Le Duc Anh at the Presidential Palace. He also held
separate talks with Vietnamese Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed a friendship and bilateral cooperation
treaty and an accord on the avoidance of double taxation this
evening.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam and Belarus established diplomatic ties in January
1992. Lukashenko is the first president of Belarus to visit
Vietnam since the disintegration of the former Soviet Union in
1991.
</P>
<P>
Belarus is the 27th largest foreign investors in Vietnam with a
38 million U.S. dollars joint-venture rubber processing plant in
the southern port of Vung Tau.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the two-way trade volume between the two countries
stood at 14.5 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam imported from Belarus machines, trucks, tires, motor
bikes, ball bearings and engines and sold Belarus rice, tea,
coffee, rubber, seafood, vegetable oil, medicinal herbs, fruit and
garments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
