<HEADLINE> ARCC Meeting for Integration of Women in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The 18th Meeting of the African
Regional Coordinating Committee for the Integration of Women in
Development (ARCC) opened here today.
</P>
<P>
In her opening address, Tadelech Haile Michael, Minister in
charge of women's affairs in the Prime Minister's Office,
stressed the importance of African countries to share their
experiences and work out a comprehensive strategy towards addressing
the pressing social, cultural, economic and political problems
confronting Africa's women today.
</P>
<P>
Tadelech called on African countries and women's organizations
to cooperate in implementation of the platforms for action of Dakar
and Beijing conferences.
</P>
<P>
''Exchange of experiences in the area of human resource develop-
ment, employment creation and an overall program to tackle the
existing social, economic and cultural situation should receive the
utmost attention,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, K. Y. Amoako, Executive Secretary
of the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), said
the meeting will provide the forum for participants to consider
proposals to strengthen women's capacity and commitment to women's
role in development.
</P>
<P>
He told participants that ECA is advocating the adoption of
national strategies to enhance women's participation in economic
transformation and development, promoting best-practices on how
to remove constraints on women, and fostering the exchange of
experiences and information among women ecnomic operators in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The ARCC was established in 1979 by the ECA Conference of
Minsiters. It is an inter-governmental policy-making body that
focuses on the advancement of women.
</P>
<P>
As such, It is the political arm of the ECA's gender program,
which is implemented by the African Center for Women (ACW). The
ARCC meets annually to review the work of the center, and to
provide it with orientation and guildance.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting will review acw's program work between
April 1996 and April 1997, discuss follow-up strategies towards
implementing the Dakar and Beijing platforms of action, and
consider the reprot on the commission on the status of women.
enditem

