<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ding Song Shocked As China Downs Slovenia 3-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 24 (Xinhua) -- World top defensive
player Ding Song suffered an upset loss to less-known Robert
Smrekar as China overcame Slovenia 3-1 at their opening men's team
match at the World Table Tennis Championships here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Smrekar, rated 115th in the world, clinched a 12-21, 21-12,
21-15 victory over the world No. 7 after China's Olympic champion
Liu Guoliang won the first game against Sasa Ignjatovic in
straight sets.
</P>
<P>
Ding looked compeletly out of form as he failed to put up his
trademark chop-and-attack game.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old Chinese jumped to international stardom in the
1995 world championships, where he won a crucial point in China's
3-2 final victory over three-time world champion Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Ding also ousted 1991 world singles champion Jorgen Persson of
Sweden and then world No. 1 Jean-Michael Saive of Beigium en route
to finishing fourth in the last Worlds.
</P>
<P>
"Ding Song is no longer a secret to Europeans," said Chinese
head coach Cai Zhenhua. "They have been studying his style since
the 1995 championships."
</P>
<P>
"I won't lose confidence on him," the Chinese coach added.
</P>
<P>
World top player Kong Linghui regained lead for China as he
outplayed Gregor Skafar 21-11, 21-13.
</P>
<P>
Liu wrapped up China's victory with a 21-15, 21-11 win over
Smrekar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
