<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Rejects DPRK's "3+1" Meeting Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 24 (xinhua) -- South Korea rejected today
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)'s "3+1" proposal that
the two sides and the United States meet first before China joins
in.
</P>
<P>
Yoo Myung-hwan, Director General of the foreign ministry's
North American Affairs Bureau, was quoted by Yonhap News Agency as
saying that the South Korean government dismissed the proposal
because it is regarded as a part of Pyongyang's strategies to
solve issues on food aid and lifting U.S.economic sanctions on it.
</P>
<P>
South Korea hoped to discuss at the peace talks fundamental
ways for the North side to get out of its economic plight and food
shortage through direct inter-Korean economic cooperation, Yoo
said.
</P>
<P>
The "3+1" proposal was put forward by DPRK representative
during the pre-Four Party Talks contact in New York on April 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
