<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Eager to Develop Close Relations With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz said here today that Iraq is eager to develop close
relations with Russia and praised the Russian efforts to try to
lift the U.N.-imposed sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Aziz stressed Iraq's eagerness when meeting with the
visiting Russian State Duma (lower house of parliament) Deputy
Speaker Sergei Baburin, Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that he appreciates Russia's support to Iraq's demands
to lift the seven-year-long embargo, which was imposed by the
U.N. Security Council after Iraq invaded Kuwait in August 1990.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister also praised the Russian State Duma
for its friendly stance toward Iraq and its on-going calls to get
the embargo lifted.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Baburin hailed Iraq's great achievements in its
reconstruction after the 1991 Gulf War and stressed that Russia
is willing to "cement ties of joint cooperation."
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Sa'eed al-
Sahaf on Wednesday morning, Baburin expressed his support to Iraq in
running pilgrims flights.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Iraq sent 104 elderly and sick pilgrims
in an aircraft to Mecca, Saudi Arabia to perform hajj. On Monday
and Tuesday, eight Iraqi military helicopters flew across the
no-fly zone in southern Iraq to an Iraqi-Saudi border area to fly
the pilgrims home.
</P>
<P>
Now the helicopters are waiting at Iraqi border city Aar'ar for
the returning of the pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
The Russian deputy speaker arrived in Baghdad on Monday with an
delegation at the invitation of the Iraqi National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The visit is designed to develop bilateral parliamentary
relations and enhance friendship and cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Russia were traditional trade partners and they
enjoyed good relationship before the Gulf War. But Russia withdrew
from the Gulf area and its influence diminished as a result of
the disintegration of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
But now Russia tries to make a come-back in this region and the
relations between the two countries are warming up. Russia and
Iraq signed "Vast Strategic Contract" on March 21 to develop
Iraq's western oil fields, which has proven reserves of almost 15
billion barrels crude oil and it is estimated to be the largest
oil field in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
