<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestine Urges Israel to Return to Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Nasser al-Kidwa, permanent
observer of Palestine to the UN, today urged Israel to stop
construction of the new colonial settlement in eastern Jerusalem
and return to the right path of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
As the first speaker at the 10th Emergency Special Session of
the General Assembly which opened here this morning, the
Palestinian observer noted the current Israeli government had
adopted basic political guidelines contradicting the agreements
signed and dangerous actions threatening the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Since its occupation in 1967 of Palestinian territory,
including Jerusalem, Israel had worked to change the legal status
and demographic composition of Jerusalem and of the occupied
Palestinian territory as a whole through the colonical settlement
of the land, he reviewed.
</P>
<P>
"This has been done in flagrant violation of the Fourth Geneva
Convention of 1949 and the Hague Regulations of 1907 and in
blatant defiance to relevant Security Council resolutions," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The right path was the implementation of the existing
agreements, including the implementation of all overdue
provisions and future obligations, the acceleration of the
negotiations for the final settlement within the framework of the
existing agreements and reaffirming compliance with those
agreements, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We affirm that we are still committed to the peace process and
the agreements reached between the parties within its framework.
We are still ready to continue implementing our obligation in this
regard," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the international community to adopt collective
measures which would guarantee the prohibition of assistance to
those who violate international law and the United Nations should
become engaged in observing the situation. All this should lead to
the immediate cessation of Israel's construction in Jabal Abu
Ghneim of eastern Jerusalem and of all other settlement
activities, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
