<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Africans Strive to Develop Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The four-day 30th meeting of
World Tourism Organization (WTO) Regional Commission for Africa
entered its second day today. Participants will have a seminar on
safety and security for African quality tourism today and tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Africa recorded a 7 percent increase in arrivals in 1996 which
amounted to 20.6 million, whereas receipts rose more steeply with 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
As sub-regional level, North Africa remains the leading inter-
national tourist destination and recorded the highest receipts. In
that sub-region, Morocco posted the best results compared to 1995,
with increases of 3.8 percent in arrivals and 9.9 percent in
receipts.
</P>
<P>
Southern Africa, which comes second, recorded a slower growth
rate with only a 3.1 percent increase in arrivals in 1996
compared to 1995, as opposed to a 17.4 increase in 1995 compared
to 1994. The same trend is observed in receipts which rose less
fast in 1996 than in 1995, at a rate of 8 percent, whereas the
growth rate in 1995 was 14.2 percent compared to 1994. South
Africa is still the sub-region's top tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
East Africa, where the fastest growth rate in arrivals in the
African region was recorded with 9 percent between 1995 and 1996,
occupies a third place. It also recorded the region's greatest gains
in tourism receipts in 1996 with 13.4 percent. Kenya recorded the
highest tourism receipts in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
West Africa recorded the second-
fastest growth rate in the African region for both arrivals and
receipts. However, central Africa remains the least-visited region.
Tourist arrivals and receipts in 1996 showed a downward trend
compared to 1995.
</P>
<P>
The above progress was the result of most African countries which
pay more attention to the industry and take a series of measures to
develop tourism. During the past year, five meetings related
to tourism were held in Africa, such as tourism training in Morocco,
tourims statistics in Morocco and Zimbabwe, the new information
technologies in Cote d'Ivoire and the management and financing of
wildlife parks for toruism in Tanzania. Meetings were also organized
in Lesotho, Tunisia, Senegal and Madagascar to promote the develop-
ment of tourism in Africa last year. A cultural tourism
program on ''the Slave Route'' was organized last year to enhance
awareness internatioanlly of the history of the slave trade and to
encourage tourists to discover the relevant sites and monuments
existing in Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, African tourism has indeed lagged behind of the world
tourism. The available statistics show that in 1996,
international tourist arrivals reached nearly 594 million, while
receipts from international travel climbed to 425 billion US
dollars. Africa's shares were only 20.6 million arrivals and 8
billion dollars receipts, representing only 3.5 percent and 1.8
percent of the world total respectively. Ethiopian President
Negasso Gidada pointed out that ''this is all the more worrying
because as we all realize, in 1975 the corresponding figure for
Africa's share was 3.1 percent of global receipt, thus indicating
the fact since then there has been a precipitate decline in what
has already been a small share that africa had in the global
tourism market.''
</P>
<P>
According to the WTO forecasts, world tourism will continue to
grow by an average of 4 percent a year for the rest of the decade to
reach 700 million international arrivals and over 600 billion
dollars by the year 2000. African countries must catch up with the
world development trend and give priority to tourism industry. As
the meeting stressed, the meaningful and effective growth and
development of the tourism industry in Africa is heavily dependent,
among others, on improvement of infrastructures, the establishment
of adequate toruism facilities and the enhancement of intra-
African tourism as well as sub-regional cooperation in marketing
and promotion. Meanwhile, matters relating to peace and security
in the continent should also be given the priority.
</P>
<P>
Of course, Africa has great potentialities for development of its
tourism. Firstly, its scenic spots and historial sites as well as
its ancient folk customs, are destinations of international
arrivals. Secondly, tourism has been become main sources of foreign
exchange for many African countries and Africans have experiences
on development the industry. Thirdly, most of African countries gave
priority to develop tourism in recent years. They increased investmen
to the industry and encourage foreign and private investment. They
also strengthen cooepration among them in the industry. Fourthly,
the political situation in the continent is going stabler and stabler
in the past years and this is the pre-condition for development of
tourism in Africa. African tourism certainly can make greater
contribution to economic development in the continent if African
countries continue to create peace environment and fully use their
natural and manpower resources. enditem

