<HEADLINE> Israel Slams UN Assembly's Debate of Har Homa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Israel today slammed the
United Nations General Assembly for holding a special debate on
its controversial Jewish settlement project in East Jerusalem's
Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Palestinian and Arab representatives, the
Assembly is holding a two-day special session late today to
debate the Har Homa project. This is the fourth time that the
international body has discussed the issue, which caused the
current deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Eitan Ben-Tsur, Director-General of Israeli Foreign Ministry,
said that the debate was "unnecessary and damaging". He criticized
the U.N. for misusing its role, stressing the differences between
Israel and the Palestinian side should only be resolved through
direct negotiations between them.
</P>
<P>
"Instead of issuing yet another condemnation of Israel, the
U.N. would be better served by using its influences to encourage
the parties to solve their differences in direct negotiations,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has already debated the Har Homa
issue twice and the General Assembly once. But the United States
vetoed two Security Council resolutions which demanded Israel to
stop the controversial housing project in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
At today's session, the Palestinian representative to the U.N.
was proposing a draft resolution calling on all countries to
bar any assistance to Israeli public and private establishments
involved in the settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
However, David Peleg, acting head of Israeli mission to the
U.N., told Israel Radio that the European Union (EU) is lobbying
for toning down the resolution. "It (the resolution) is expected
to be more moderate as a result of the EU lobbying efforts," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the speakers will emphasize their support to the peace
process, and we will not support the draft resolution, which has
been prepared, which is very one-sided," he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel began the Jewish Settlement construction work in Har Homa
of southeastern Jerusalem in late March, despite strong Palestinian
protests and international pressure. The peace process has since
grounded to a halt, leading to violent clashes between
stone-throwing Palestinian protesters and Israeli soldiers across
the Palestinian territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
