<HEADLINE> EAC Summit to Be Held in Arusha Next Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April (Xinhua) -- Heads of state of the East African
Co-operation (EAC) made up of Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda, are expected
to meet in Arusha, Northern Tanzania on Tuesday next week.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry statement issued here today said the summit will
take stock of efforts made towards enhanced regional co-operation
since the EAC was formally launched a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The one-day summit will also chart out future program of the
co-operation.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the Sub-Committee of Experts started meeting in
Arusha today to lay ground work for the summit to be followed on April
27 by a meeting of the Co-Ordinating Committe made up of principal or
permanent secretaries.
</P>
<P>
It said the heads of state will consider a report outlining
achievments that have been realised in the co-operation over the past
one year and endorse the proposed EAC Development Strategy for
1997/2000.
</P>
<P>
"The strategy lays foundation for the translation of vision of the
co-operation into a comprehensive action program, spelling out
priority areas and time-frame for implementation," the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
The statement further said the main emphasis of the strategy is a
mid-term program establishing a single market and investment area for
the region and giving priority to development of regional economic
infrastructure and enhancement of technical capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Since the formal launching of EAC last year, moves towards enhanced
co-operation have been implemented in several areas including
immigration, finance, security, communications and transport, labour,
touurism, higher education and co-operation among national assemblies
of the three countries.  enditem

