<HEADLINE> Mobutu-Kabila Talks Could Be Decided Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Ye Xingzen)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Time and venue for the
long-awaited direct peace talks between Zairean President Mobutu
Sese Seko and rebel leader Laurent Kabila could be determined
soon, said South African Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Assembly in Cape Town today, Pahad
said Kabila had reiterated his commitment to the South African
government on Wednesday that he is willing to meet Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mobutu's special envoy Honore Ngbanda arrived in
South Africa on Wednesday to convey a message to Deputy President
Thabo Mbeki that the Zairean government also remained committed
to such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, now remains only the question of when and where the
talks should be held, said the South African deputy foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
He also said the South African government would have
consultations with Mahomed Sahnoun, United Nations Special Envoy
to Zaire and the Great Lakes region, and other interested
role-players to "finally determine the time and venue for this
very important summit."
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun was expected to return to South Africa tonight from
his visit to Angola and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports indicated that Mobutu was willing to meet
Kabila, but the 66-year-old ailing president might not travel to
South Africa for the talks because of his ill health.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, the United Nations and the Organization of
African Unity all showed their beliefs that a negotiated solution
in Zaire was in the interest of all Zaireans, and the planned
talks were necessary to achieve a political solution to the
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
