<HEADLINE> Egyptian Security Court Tries Israeli Spy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli textile worker and an
Egyptian charged with spying for the Jewish state stood trial at
the Egyptian Higher State Security Court today amid tight
security.
</P>
<P>
The court, after opening the first hearing, decided to adjourn
the case to May 18 while keeping the defendants in detention.
</P>
<P>
Azam Azam, a 35-year-old chief mechanic at an Israeli-owned
factory in Egypt, and Egyptian teacher Emad Abdul Hamid Ismail of
34, another defendant in the espionage case, pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
Azam, speaking from behind the bars at the first hearing
today, told reporters that he "is well-treated in prison" and has
been visited by his relatives and Israeli embassy officials here.
</P>
<P>
Azam, dressed in a long white robe, appeared in good health.
</P>
<P>
Ismail seemed a bit disturbed while swearing that the was
innocent, but he joined with Azam in expressing his confidence in
the "integrity" of the Egyptian judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli women, Zahra Yousef Greis and Mona Ahmed Shawahna,
who are at large in Israel, were tried in absentia with Azam and
Ismail.
</P>
<P>
Policemen in riot gear were deployed inside and outside the
courtroom in the Bab el-Khalq area, which was crowded with
foreign and local reporters and people interested in the case.
</P>
<P>
The indictment bill said that Azam gave Ismail women's
underwar soaked in invisible ink to be used in sending secret
messages to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Ismail was charged with helping the two women spies for
Israel's intelligence service Mossad in return for 1,000
U.S. dollars a month when he went to Israel in 1996 to conduct
training at a women's garments factory.
</P>
<P>
The bill demanded the arrest of Greis and Shawahna and asked
for the harshest possible penalty for all the defendants, which
would be life imprisonment with hard labor.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to have made peace with Israel
but the ties have been cool. The spy case fueled the mounting
tensions between Arabs and Israelis because of the deadlocked
Mideast peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
