<HEADLINE> Last Batch of Turkish Troops Leaves for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The last convoy of Turkish
troops today left the Aegean city of Izmir for Albania to join a
multinational protection force to maintain security there, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported this evening.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that this was the third batch of the Turkish
troops to go to Albania within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
The 310-strong Turkish force went to Tirana, capital of
Albania, by three airplanes of the Turkish Airlines for the
"Mission Alba," a move organized by the United Nations in a bid
to protect the security of Tirana.
</P>
<P>
The first convoy of a 153-strong Turkish troops and six
vehicles went to Tirana by air last Wednesday and the second
batch of a 246-strong force together with four military ships
went to Albania last Sunday by sea.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is assigned to take charge of the security of Tirana,
the Tirana Airport and the northern part of Albania, and the
Turkish contingent is commanded by Marine Colonel Suleyman Bozkurt
with troops selected from specially-trained marine and commandos
of the Turkish Navy.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish press reported that Turkey has also planned to
send cargo aircraft three times a month to the Balkan state in
an effort to provide continuous logistics support for its
contingent there. 
</P>
