<HEADLINE> Traffic Through Beira Corridor to Be Boosted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Traffic through Zimbabwe's
eastern gateway to the sea is expected to get a boost this year
from increased economic ties between the country and its
neighbor, Mozambique, the Beira Corridor Group (BCG) said today.
</P>
<P>
BCG Liaison Director Christopher Motley said the group, which
coordinates movement of traffic to the Mozambican port of Beira,
expected more Zimbabweans to use the corridor as several
bilateral agreements between the two neighbors came into effect.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe and Mozambique recently signed a joint commission
agreement which, among other things, cleared the way for the
long-awaited preferential trade agreement between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Satisfactory progress has also been made on the issue of road
transit and border charges and the transport ministers from both
sides are expected to meet next month to finalize negotiations on
a road transport services agreement.
</P>
<P>
Beira Port on the Indian Ocean handles cargo to and from the
southern African hinterland which ranges from foodstuff to coal.
</P>
<P>
It offers an important alternative route to the sea for goods
from landlocked Botswana, Malawi, Zambia and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
