<HEADLINE> Opinion Polls Show Labor Still Well Ahead of Tory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The opinion polls conducted by
Gallup and MORI showed Labor's lead is still well ahead of Tories
at 20 and 21 points respectively, which contradicts an ICM poll
Tuesday showing it slipping to 5 points.
</P>
<P>
According to Gallup today, voters still think opposition leader
Tony Blair would make a better prime minister than John Major, are
still convinced Labor would manage the economy better than the
Tories and still prefer Labor to the Tories.
</P>
<P>
Equally important, the "fear factor" continues to work strongly
in Labor's favor.
</P>
<P>
Large numbers of people are worried about the possible
consequences of a Labor government under Blair but they are even
more worried about the possible consequences of a fifth
consecutive Tory government.
</P>
<P>
Gallup's findings also suggest that Labor support has remained
remarkably steady since the campaign began.
</P>
<P>
In the 18 rounds of the rolling poll so far, the proportion of
voters backing Labor has never risen above 53 percent or fallen
below 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to today's MORI's poll, more than a quarter of the
public believe that it is time for a change at this election, even
though "the government has built strong foundations for Britain's
economic recovery."
</P>
<P>
This reflected in a break in the traditionally close link
between changes in the MORI economic optimism index and in levels
of party support.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the break, observers here said that this is the
most worrying finding for the Tories in view of the strength of
the economy and the improvement in the "feel-good" factor.
</P>
<P>
It indicates that many voters are determined to get rid of the
Tories almost regardless of other influences, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
