<HEADLINE> Liberia's Taylor Denies Hidding Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Former Liberian warlord Charles
Taylor said today that he knew nothing about the hidden weapons
found by west Africa's peacekeeping force, ECOMOG, in a town
previously controlled by his faction.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG announced on Wednesday it discovered a large quantity
of hidden arms in Nimba County bordering Cote d'Voire, including
bombs and ammunitions, anti-aircraft guns, 105 mm guns and
anti-tank guns.
</P>
<P>
But Taylor said: "I know nothing about the hidden arms and
ammunition, and we dissociate ourselves from this act."
</P>
<P>
"This country must be weapon-free, and we encourage those who
may know about hidden arms anywhere in the country to report them
to ECOMOG," he said on a radio station he controls in Monrovia,
capital of Liberia.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here said that the hidden arms and
ammunition were found in the northeastern border village of
Butuo, through which Taylor and his disbanded National Patriotic
Front of Liberia militia launched the civil war from Cote d'Voire
on December 24, 1989.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Commander Major-General Victor Malu said on Wednesday
that his force was still interrogating the persons found guarding
the weapons, and that once enough information was gathered,
Charles Taylor would be summoned for questioning.
</P>
<P>
Malu declined to mention what action he would take if Taylor
was eventually implicated, but said that the situation would not
be a threat to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
After the January 30 deadline for Liberian faction fighters to
surrenders their arms, the peacekeepers in early March discovered
several trucks of arms in the house of Alhaji Kromah, leader of
another former warring faction, the United Liberation Movement.
</P>
<P>
Kromah was first arrested and to be prosecuted but was later
pardoned by ECOMOG for the sake of the continuance of the peace
process in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
Both Taylor and Kromah have resigned as vice-chairmen of
Liberia's ruling Council of State to run for the presidency in
the general elections scheduled for coming May 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
