<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Makes New Pledge for Senate Approval of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today promised the Senate that he would withdraw from the Chemical
Weapons Treaty if the the pact inadvertently results in the spread
of of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the guarantee in a letter to Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott in order to gain the ratification of the treaty
by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Lott said, "This commitment is
unprecedented." The assurances had affected his thinking although
he still remained uncommitted on how to vote for the pact, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Lott and Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, have been lobbying for not approving the treaty,
demanding amendments to the document.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is expected to vote later today on the convention,
which is to take effect on April 29 with or without the U.S.'
participation. A two-thirds majority would be needed for
approval.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Clinton said he was "prepared to withdraw from
the treaty" if other countries used its provisions to proliferate
chemical weapons technology and endanger U.S. security.
</P>
<P>
Article 10 and 11 of the treaty require contracting parties to
provide chemical weapons defenses and call for exchanges of
peaceful chemicals and technology among the parties.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's letter aims easing the concerns of the opponents
about the provisions. Lott and Helms insist that some countries
may use the provisions to spread poison gas and attack the U.S.
chemical weapons technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
