<HEADLINE> UK World Trade Gap Widens in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Britain's global trade deficit
widened to 758 million pounds (1.2 billion US dollars) in February
from January's 535 million pound (872 million dollar) shortfall,
which was revised down from 641 million pounds (1.04 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics said today that the figures
were lower than analysts' forecast of a gap of 813 million pounds
(1.3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Exports in February fell by 1.4 percent to 14.164 billion
pounds (23 billion dollars) while imports rose by 0.2 percent to
14.992 billion pounds (24.4 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Economists said that this was the first official data to show
clearly that exports are suffering as the strength of sterling
makes British goods more expensive abroad.
</P>
<P>
The figures were in line with recent business surveys showing
that exports orders were in decline. 
</P>
