<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech President Rejects Return of Sudeten-Germans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Czech President Vaclav
Havel today ruled out the return of Sudeten-Germans who were
expelled from former Czechoslovakia in 1945.
</P>
<P>
He told the German parliament Bundestag in a speech that his
country could not accept the return of Sudeten-Germans.
</P>
<P>
"Just as Germany today cannot bring back to life tens of
thousands of Czech Nazi victims and turn the clock back to
1938..., the Czech Republic cannot give back the old homeland of
the expelled Germans," said Havel.
</P>
<P>
Former Czechoslovakia expelled about 3 million Sudeten-Germans
from territories where they had lived for centuries after World
War II. They were accused of having been traitors backing Adolf
Hitler's carve-up and occupation of the country since 1938.
</P>
<P>
In the opinion of Sudeten-Germans, their expulsion was a case
of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
In a welcoming speech for Havel, parliamentary leader Rita
Suessmuth noted that a natural resolution of the issue could be
expected after the Czech Republic was admitted into the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
EU citizens can settle and work in any of the EU member states.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic, Poland and Hungary are the most likely to
become new EU and NATO members.
</P>
<P>
Today in Prague, the Czech press agency CTK reported that
Jewish leaders boycotted the Havel speech in protest, saying that
Germany's financial compensation for Czech-Jews subjected to Nazi
persecution was insufficient.
</P>
<P>
The compensation totaling 165 million marks (96 million US
dollars) for Nazi victims in the Czech Republic was pledged in a
German-Czech joint declaration signed earlier this year by German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus, in
which both countries expressed regret for the excesses of the
past.
</P>
<P>
The document, which was approved by Bundestag last February,
has been greeted in Germany except by Sudetens, who were irritated
by the accord's failure to mention their right to resettlement in
the Czech Republic and measures for making up their losses of
properties.
</P>
<P>
Havel today also hailed the joint declaration in his address,
saying the accord had liberated German-Czech relations and created
a foundation for improving bilateral cooperation at the European
level. The Czech president called for efforts towards better
future relations between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
