<HEADLINE> Unity of Lebanese Labor Unions Threatened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The unity of Lebanon's powerful
Confederation of Trade Unions (CTU) was threatened following today's
elections in which both two candidates for the chairmanship, one
backed by the government and another an outspoken dissenter,
claimed victory.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the outcome of the elections at a press conference,
Minister of Labor Assaad Hardan described the polls in which the
pro-government trade unionist Ghaneem Zoghbi came out as a winner
as "legitimate."
</P>
<P>
"The elections which were held under the supervision of the
labor ministry were legitimate and what they resulted were
legitimate," Hardan said, noting that the elections were the only
one held "according to the rules and under the legal roof."
</P>
<P>
Zoghbi announced that 33 of totally 54 representatives from 27
trade unions voted in his favor, making him the new chairman
of the CTU.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the polls started in the confederation's
headquarters at exactly 11:00 a.m. (08:00 GMT) as scheduled and
under the Labor Ministry's supervision.
</P>
<P>
Elias Abu Rizk, the CTU's incumbent chairman, however,
announced that he obtained 24 votes from 44 representatives of 22
trade unions in the polls which were held hours before the
government-sponsored elections started.
</P>
<P>
"The labor ministry did not intervene because there was no role
for it in these elections and other elections except these are
illegal," added Abu Rizk, who has reportedly caused repeated
headaches for the government of Prime Minister Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
Since Wednesday night, the government launched a tight security
dragnet across central Beirut, sealing off all approaches to the
CTU's headquarters at the residential neighborhood there.
</P>
<P>
Only officials of the Labor Ministry and the CTU were allowed
to get through the cordon to take part in what the leftist
Beirut daily As-Safir called an "unprecedented bone-breaking
showdown" between the government and the current leftist
leadership of the confederation under Abu Rizk.
</P>
<P>
Just five days before the elections taking place, the
ministry declared the admission of five new trade unions into the
confederation, upping the number of the 44-man electoral caucus to
54, a move which would inevitably strip Abu Rizk of any chance to
win the competition.
</P>
<P>
The desperate Abu Rizk claimed that the admission was unlawful
and insisted only the 44 representatives of the original 22 trade
unions be eligible voters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
