<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The prosecution today opened
its case in Denver against Oklahoma City bombing defendant Timothy
McVeigh, accusing him of murdering innocent men, women and
children in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Chief prosecutor Joseph Hartzler told the jury of seven men and
five women that McVeigh wanted to send a message.
</P>
<P>
"The truck (carrying the bomb) was there to impose the will of
Timothy McVeigh on the rest of America," media reports quoted
Hartzler as telling the jurors.
</P>
<P>
He said McVeigh was going to carry out his plan "by murdering
innocent men, women and children... to see blood flow in the
streets of America."
</P>
<P>
McVeigh is accused of bombing the Alfred P. Murrah federal
government building on April 19, 1995, killing 168 people,
including 19 children. He has pleaded not guilty and faces death
if convicted.
</P>
<P>
Security was heavy today around the federal complex that houses
the courthouse in downtown Denver.
</P>
<P>
Federal Judge Richard Matsch explained the procedure of the
trial. He said that a television camera in the courtroom did not
show jurors' faces and was only telecasting the proceedings by
closed circuit to Oklahoma City. 
</P>
