<HEADLINE> US Republicans Urge More New Members in NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A group of U.S. House of
Representatives Republicans today introduced a bill calling for
membership of Romania, Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"It is critical that such countries not be left in any security
vacuum," said Benjamin Gilman, one of the bill's sponsors and
chairman of the International Relations Committee of the House.
</P>
<P>
"Our bill goes on to express the sense of Congress that
Romania, Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania should be invited to join
NATO as soon as they satisfy all of the relevant criteria," Gilman
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The bill would require President Bill Clinton to seek NATO
membership for the countries and provide aid to help them meet
military and democratic policy requirements for NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
The bill would also declare U.S. policy against NATO's pledge
not to station nuclear weapons or permanent combat troops in the
new members.
</P>
<P>
Gilman said they introduced the bill because they "worry that
in the rush to mollify Russia, concessions may be made that could
jeopardize European security and the effectiveness of NATO" and
nations that may be left out of the first round of expansion could
be "in a security vacuum."
</P>
<P>
The alliance is to invite the first group of countries, most
likely Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic and Slovenia to join in
July at its special summit in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
Russia, which is strongly opposed to the expansion, is
negotiating an agreement with NATO to set their future relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
