<HEADLINE> Bosnian Croat Leaders Unhappy with Izetbegovic Letter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Top Bosnian Croat officials on
Thursday complained that the Muslim partners had not consulted
with them in sending a letter to the international community on
the implementation of the Dayton peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Kresimir Zubak, the Croat member of the Bosnian president,
Neven Tomic, deputy co-chairman of the council of ministers and
foreign minister Jadranko Prlic, said that they had learned only
through media that Alija Izetbegovic, chairman of the presidency
and Haris Silajdzic presented the letter to representatives of the
Contact Group and other international circles on April 21.
</P>
<P>
The letter by Izetbegovic and Silajdzic expressed their
concerns over the slow implementation of Dayton peace accords.
</P>
<P>
The complaint by Croat leaders was raised in their letter to
the same representatives of the international community, according
to local TV and press reports.
</P>
<P>
The Croats' letter said that since no Croat official
participated in the drafting of the Izetbegovic-Silajdzic letter,
it represented only the position of one constitutive nation.
</P>
<P>
The Croat leaders also stressed that they did not agree with
all the stances in the letter presented by the Muslim side, who
listed nine areas where provisions of the Dayton accords are
either violated or implemented slowly.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the Croat leaders' letter, Silajdzic said that
the differences between Croats and Muslims with regard to the
subject are more of style than in content. 
</P>
</TEXT>
