<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-24 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemeni President on Parliamentary Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh
reiterated here today that the parliamentary elections, due on
Sunday, will be conducted in a free and clean atmosphere on the
basis of equality among all political parties and forces in Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference, President Saleh said that
international observers from a number of friendly countries and
other non-governmental organizations will supervise the elections.
</P>
<P>
He said the new house of representatives to replace the old one
will embrace 301 members.
</P>
<P>
On the future of Yemen after elections, and the impact of the
boycott of elections by the Yemeni Socialist party, Saleh said
"the future of Yemen is bright."
</P>
<P>
He added that by boycotting the elections or the democratic
process, the main opposition Socialist party is isolating itself.
</P>
<P>
"We have welcomed the Socialist party and tried to help it ever
since July 7, 1994, when it proclaimed war and separation," said
the president.
</P>
<P>
On reports that the ruling People's Congress Party and its
coalition partner the Islah Party have already divided the
constituences between them, the president said the two parties
will coordinate during the elections.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that all will be done to prevent any
friction from undermining the safety and cleanliness of the
election process.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary elections in Yemen will be contested by 12
parties for 301 seats.
</P>
<P>
Four parties are boycotting the elections -- namely, the Yemen
Socialist Party, the Unionist Grouping party, the League of
Yemenites, and the Union of Popular Forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
