<HEADLINE> Joint Jordanian-US Military Committee Concludes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The joint Jordanian-U.S. military
committee concluded its works here today after reaching an
agreement preliminarily on providing Jordan with further military
requirements.
</P>
<P>
An official Jordanian source who declined to be named described
the two-day talks as successful and fruitful, saying that the
U.S. side had expressed the readiness to respond to all of
Jordan's military requests, in accordance with a definite program
to be examined later.
</P>
<P>
The same source affirmed that the two parties had worked out
a joint program for land, naval and air force exercises during the
current year, adding the scenes of these military exercises as
well as the volume of the participating forces had also been
determined.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the U.S. side had stressed during the
talks that the U.S. Administration was committed to its pledges
to deliver 16 fully-equipped F-16 fighters to Jordan and to
consider additional equipment to the warplanes before the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
The current session of the committee was jointly chaired by
Field Marshal Abdul Hafiz Mara'i Al Qaabana, chief of the General
Staff of the Royal Armed Forces of Jordan, and by Fred Smith,
U.S. First Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for
International Security Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Smith arrived in the Jordanian capital of Amman Tuesday heading
an official delegation of the U.S. Defense and State Departments,
and left here this evening upon the conclusion of the talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. provided Jordan with a C-130H military cargo plane
last February, and in December last year, it also delivered arms
worth 100 million dollars to its Arab ally, including 18
helicopters, 50 tanks, military vehicles, two boats, 100
binoculars for night military reconnaissance, besides other
equipment, rifles and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
In fact, U.S. President Bill Clinton has pledged to offer
300-million-U.S. dollar military assistance to strengthen the
capability of the Jordanian Armed Force.
</P>
<P>
The Arab kingdom has been granted non-NATO alliance status,
enabling it with more access to U.S. military equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
