<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Form Independent Auditing Standards System by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Since 1994, the Chinese Institute
of Certified Public Accountants (CICPA) has been busy setting
China's Independent Auditing Standards (CIASs) for the country's
certified public accountants.
</P>
<P>
So far, two sets of standards comprised of 27 rules have been
published, and the whole CIAS system is expected to be completed
around the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jianming, Deputy Director of the Standards Division of
CICPA, made the announcement today in Beijing at the opening of an
international symposium titled "Into the 21st Century -- China's
Economic Reform and Liberalization of Accounting Services."
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Chen outlined China's current efforts to
formulate CIASs. In 1994, CICPA established a special task force,
China's Independent Auditing Standards Group, to carry out the
work, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
He said that the objectives of setting CIASs include
establishing authoritative standards for Chinese public
accountants in performing independent audits, meant to define
their responsibilities and safeguard the legitimate rights and
interests of the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
The group has consulted local accounting institutes and other
departments across the country during the process of formulating
the rules, Chen said. The group has always worked to introduce
mainstream international practices, adapt to China's situation and
give priority to international standards, he noted.
</P>
<P>
His speech also covered the differences between CIASs and
international standards.
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar is jointly sponsored by CICPA and the Hong
Kong Society of Accountants. Participants include Chinese and
overseas accounting experts and senior officials from the Chinese
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
