<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Visits Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto is scheduled to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton
here at noon today and discuss bilateral relations including
defense and trade issues.
</P>
<P>
Kunihiko Saito, Japan's ambassador in Washington, has said that
Hashimoto's talks with Clinton will cover four large areas. Apart
from the bilateral relationship, they will discuss Asia-Pacific
issues and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the 100,000 U.S. troops deployed in Asia are
based in Japan. Moreover, Japan's ports and military airfields
would become as vital to the United States in a regional emergency
as did Saudi Arabian facilities during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Hashimoto and Clinton are expected to discuss a
longer-term review of U.S.-Japanese defense cooperation guidelines
that is slated to be completed by fall.
</P>
<P>
Trade issue is also expected on the agenda as the U.S. trade
deficit with Japan, though falling by 19 percent last year, is
likely to widen again due largely to a weak yen that makes
Japanese products cheaper and a strong dollar that makes U.S.-made
goods more expensive.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has urged Hashimoto in a letter to stabilize Tokyo's
financial system and reduce the country's trade deficit with the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
