<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baker Arrives in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- United Nations envoy to the
Western Sahara James Baker arrived here this morning from the
Moroccan capital Rabat on a short visit to Algeria for talks with
the country's leaders.
</P>
<P>
Baker was received at the Algiers International Airport by
Algerian Foreign Minister Ahmed Attaf.
</P>
<P>
His tour of the region aims to conduct consultations with the
leaders of the region on obstacles facing the peace plan which was
initiated by the U.N. in 1992 to settle the Western Sahara
dispute, according to informed sources.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has long been pushing for a referendum among the
Western Saharans to determine if the former Spanish colony should
be independent from or intergrate with Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Morocco claims the vast desert territory was part of Morocco
long before Spanish colonization and wants to base the referendum
among the land's current population.
</P>
<P>
However, the Polisario Front, which has been locked in a war
with Morocco for decades, insists the vote should be held among
74,000 residents counted in a 1974 Spanish census.
</P>
<P>
The Polisario Front is believed to have enjoyed support from
Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Addressing reporters upon his arrival at the airport, Baker
said he would offer new proposals worked out by the U.N. Secretary
General on the Western Sahara peace process. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Baker, former United States Secretary of State, was nominated
by U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan special envoy to the Western
Sahara with a view to getting the region out of the prevailing
no-peace no-war state.
</P>
<P>
The projected referendum was originally scheduled for 1992, but
the row among parties concerned delayed the process. The
U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution in March 1993, urging
the polling to be held by the end of that year. However, it
remains on paper so far.
</P>
<P>
Algiers is Baker's second leg in the tour, which will also lead
him to Mauritania.
</P>
<P>
Baker held talks over the past two days with Moroccan King
Hassan II and Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Abdullatif
Al-Filali. The talks were seen as a new U.N.move to push forward
the peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, no details of the meetings were given.
</P>
<P>
Baker is scheduled to table a report on his tour to Annan
before the U.N. Security Council meets next month to decide on the
destination of the U.N. peace-keeping troops in the Western
Sahara. The term of the mission ends in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
