<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Talks About Tasks for Education (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Education reform is the key to
achieving China's goal for education development by the end of the
century, Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said today in a public lecture.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid progress made in education since China adopted
the reform and opening-up policy in 1978, the country has set the
overall goal of first popularizing the nine-year compulsory
education system and eradicating illiteracy among young and
middle-aged people by the end of the century, Li said.
</P>
<P>
"This will lay the foundation for China's endeavor to improve
the quality of the whole nation and cultivate trans-century
personnel," noted Li, who is also a member of the Political Bureau
of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that limited education funding presents the
biggest obstacle to accomplishing this goal in China, a developing
country with the world's largest population, and reform of its
education system to improve quality and efficiency is the only
solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the eastern part of the country has nearly
reached the goal, and the government will focus its efforts on the
12 provinces in the central and western parts starting this year.
</P>
<P>
A major issue in elementary education is the shift from
"education aimed at achieving high exam scores" to "education for
improvement of students' quality," which is urgently needed for
China's elementary education system and is also a far-reaching
transformation goal in the field, the vice-premier pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that elementary education should be aimed at
developing all-round qualities in students, such as moral
standards, academic achievement, cultural accomplishments and
physical condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Talks About Tasks for Education (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the importance of occupational education, Li called it a
pillar for economic development in China.
</P>
<P>
He urged all of society to support the development of
occupational education, which is "of great significance to giving
the young more chances to become useful people, providing more job
opportunities, and helping deepen the reform of enterprises."
</P>
<P>
Under the overall planning and management of the government, he
added, enterprises, institutions and other social sectors are
responsible for establishing occupational training facilities in
China, with proper funding and support and other means from the
government.
</P>
<P>
China aims to have 60 percent to 70 percent of its middle
school graduates receive middle-level occupational education and
training, 30 to 40 percent of them enter high schools, and 40
percent of high school graduates admitted into colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the ongoing reform of the management over college
education, the vice-premier remarked, the quality and efficiency
of colleges and universities are being improved as a result of a
more reasonable distribution of teaching resources.
</P>
<P>
He called on leaders in different regions and government
departments, as well as those in colleges and universities, to
continue to promote the reform.
</P>
<P>
A good education system relies on qualified teachers, Li
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The key to improving teachers' overall quality is better
professional education for teachers, on-the-job training, and
sending more qualified young cadres in government departments to
help with teaching in less-developed areas for a certain period of
time, he added.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier urged government departments to show more
concern for teachers' working and living conditions, including
ensuring salaries not below the standards for public servants as
stipulated by law, timely payment of wages, and adequate housing.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 to 1996, China invested nearly 37 billion yuan (4.46
billion US dollars) in building some 740,000 apartments for
teachers, improving the average per capita housing space for
teachers' families from 6.6 sq m in 1992 to the present eight sq
m., according to the vice-premier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
