<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, April 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TULA, Russia -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin today
called for further increase of cultural exchanges between China
and Russia. Jiang made the call during a visit to the former
residence, now a museum, of the late Russian writer Lev Tolstoy,
which locates in the Tula region, about 200 kilometers south of
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
BONN -- China and Germany concluded here the first session of
the Chinese-German Dialogue Forum for High-Technology. The forum,
initiated by Chinese President Jiang Zemin and German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl, is designed to boost high-tech policy exchange and
provide a venue for research institutes and enterprises to explore
high-tech cooperation projects and their commercialization.
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- South Africa would bring new strength and dynamism
to the Lome Convention between the European Union (EU) and
African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) countries, said Joao de Deus
Pinheiro, EU commissioner for relations with ACP countries. He
made the comment in Luxembourg after the EU and ACP countries had
agreed on the terms for South Africa's membership of the Lome
Convention.
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia has turned down repeated request by
Israel for diplomatic ties as it is not satisfied with the
latter's attitude toward Palestine, Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad said today. "We've said it that we shall not have
diplomatic ties with them until they honor their agreement not to
be hostile to the Palestinians," he said.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's exports are expected to rebound rapidly
from its long setbacks as prices of its key export items have
recovered, the Finance and Economy Ministry said today. The
optimistic forecast was based on the recovering price of
petrochemical and steel products, semiconductors and other key
items, ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Explosions have rocked one of Britain's busiest
motorways which had been closed after a series of coded warnings
early today. Police said the affected section of M6 through
Birmingham, a big city in central England, had been shut down.
There have been no reported casualties.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- South African President Nelson Mandela has
expressed his determination to provide Syria with arms despite
opposition from the U.S., today's Syrian newspaper Al Thawra
reported. The paper said that Mandela said in an interview with
Kuwaiti daily Al Qabas published Thursday that "we owe Syria a big
debt and we have to express our gratitude by providing it with
arms needed to defend itself."
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Albanian Foreign Minister Arjan Starova said here today
that he did not regard restoration of a monarchy in Albania as
likely. "There is a very slight possibility for that, but I don't
think such a choice will be made," Starova said after talks with
his German counterpart Klaus Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France today called on the French nationals living in
Zaire to leave the country, as the Zairean rebels led by
Laurent-Desire Kabila continue to move ahead in their conquest of
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
