<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Optimistic over China's Economy Development in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Experts from top Chinese
universities and the state economic management departments have
expressed their optimism over the country's economic development
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
They believe that the national economic goal of advancement
based on stability will be reached, and China's economy will be
ushered into a new era characterized by stable growth at an
"appropriately rapid speed."
</P>
<P>
They expressed their views at the "Spring Seminar on
Forecasting 1997 Economic Situations" which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
According to their analysis, there are a number of favorable
conditions for China's economic growth in 1997:
</P>
<P>
-- pressure of high inflation is eased after three years'
macro-economic control, and the country's "relatively stringent
financial policy" has shown its effectiveness;
</P>
<P>
-- market demands have been increased and are expected to rise
continuously;
</P>
<P>
-- major grain harvests in 1995 and 1996 have provided
sufficient guarantees for industrial production and rising of
people's living standards;
</P>
<P>
-- industries of transportation, energy and communications have
been strengthened to ease China's long-time bottleneck of the
development of the national economy;
</P>
<P>
-- foreign reserve has been up, which leaves the central
government better equipped to make use of the international market
and conduct macro-level economic control; and
</P>
<P>
-- the world economy is picking up, which is also conducive to
the sustained, rapid and healthy development of China's national
economy.
</P>
<P>
Scholars also pointed out the problems and contradictions China
still faces, such as the inability of quite a number of
state-owned enterprises to adapt to the market, as well as the
similarities of many places in regard to economic structure.
</P>
<P>
The annual seminars on forecasting China's economic development
 have been co-sponsored by the State Statistics Bureau, the China
Academy of Social Sciences and several economic management
departments of the state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
