<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Vows to Bring Maglev Train in Operation in 2005 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- German Transportation Minister
Matthias Wissmann today reaffirmed Bonn's commitment to the
construction of a magnetic levitation rail link between Hamburg
and Berlin despite the soaring costs and an uncertain market.
</P>
<P>
"Despite all the nay-saying, the Transrapid is on course,"
Wissmann said, referring to the high-speed magnetic levitation
train designed by a German engineer which can run at about 400
kilometer per hour.
</P>
<P>
Germany has been planning to build a 292-kilometer high-speed
railway link between Hamburg and Berlin using the Transrapid
train, which would cover the distance in about one hour.
</P>
<P>
However, a revised project study issued by Wissmann Friday
showed that the investment costs of the project would run up to
9.8 billion marks (5.7 billion U.S. dollars), 10 percent higher
than previously projected.
</P>
<P>
The report also lowered projections of annual revenues from
1.15 billion marks (670 million dollars) to between 700 to 900
million marks (411 to 529 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Concerned about the future of the Transrapid link, three
construction firms have announced their pullout of the project,
leaving the private consortium which would operate the Transrapid
with just three companies -- Thyssen Industrie, Siemens and
Adtranz.
</P>
<P>
Under the revised plan, instead of the three construction
companies, now the German Railways (DB) will be in charge of
building the track, for which the German federal government will
provide 6.1 billion marks (3.5 billion dollars) in financing.
</P>
<P>
Wissmann said construction of the track would be opened to
European partners, with the DB serving as the contractor.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the DB would operate and market the overall
Transrapid system, Wissmann said, adding that the new concept had
been backed by Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Finance Minister Theo
Waigel.
</P>
<P>
Opponents to the Transrapid include economic and transportation
experts who voiced concern over its costs and its ability to
attract enough passengers. Backers, however, believe that the
Transrapid could be a potential export hit.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the controversies, Wiessmann said the project would
create 18,000 jobs during the construction phase and 4,400
permanent jobs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
