<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bell Canada to Build Own Giant R&AMP;D Lab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Canada's largest telephone company
Bell Canada will launch its own software research and development
lab within six weeks, according to president John McLennan.
</P>
<P>
Though details on the size or budget of the lab has not been
revealed, the lab will rank as "Canada's second-largest privately
owned R&AMP;D complex," McLennan was quoted as saying by today's Globe
and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Bell is ready to invest "dramatically more money in R&AMP;D than
ever before," McLennan noted.
</P>
<P>
The paper said it would need a budget in the hundreds of
millions of dollars to be a player with the scope envisaged by the
president.
</P>
<P>
Bell Canada now owns a 30-percent stake in Canada's largest
private R&AMP;D complex, Ottawa-based Bell-Northern Research Ltd.
(BNR).
</P>
<P>
BNR employs over 17,000 scientists, engineers and technologists
worldwide and of that 9,000 are employed in Canada. Its budget
last year was more than 1.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The proposed software lab won't be as large, but its
establishment stands to rank as one of most pivotal events for
Canada's high-tech sector since BNR was created.
</P>
<P>
Several factors have propelled Bell to form its own software
lab, including the advent of local competition, growth of the
Internet, the reduction of long-distance prices and greater
choices for consumers.
</P>
<P>
Apart from creating new services for all of Canada's telephone
companies, the new lab will also generate numerous spinoffs and
tap lucrative export markets, McLennan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
