<HEADLINE> China, Germany Conclude First Session of High-Tech Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China and Germany concluded here
today the first session of the Chinese-German Dialogue Forum for
High-Technology, which started on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The forum was initiated by Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. It is designed to boost high-tech
policy exchange between the two governments, and to provide a
venue for research institutes and enterprises to explore high-tech
cooperation projects and their commercialization.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from both sides have worked out a group of priority
cooperation projects and possible joint projects in the fields of
electronics, coal processing, chemical production and
environmental protection, said Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
A summary of the meeting was signed here today by Chen Jinhua,
minister in charge of China's State Planning Commission, German
Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt and Research Minister Juergen
Ruettgers.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also agreed to hold the next round of talks in
Beijing next year.
</P>
<P>
Some industrialists and representatives from leading research
institutes of both countries attended the three-day session.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Chen also met with German Vice-Chancellor and
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said Bonn supports the high-tech dialogue forum and
hopes that the forum would give a boost to further development of
economic and technological cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation will visit some large enterprises in
Berlin and Munich, then leave for Beijing on April 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
