<HEADLINE> Dhaka Likely to Attain Self-Sufficiency in Salt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is likely to attain
self-sufficiency in salt this year as has been indicated by the
producers from different areas, industry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Salt production in Dutubdia, Maheskhali, Teknaf and Chokoria of
Chittagong and Cox's Bazar salt regions has already reached
523,ooo metric tons from December last to this month, said an
official of Bangladesh Small and Cottage Industries Corporation
(BSCIC).
</P>
<P>
"The salt production rate is quite satisfactory," the official
said, adding that more than 300,000 tons of salt was expected to
be produced over the next two months if weather remains favorable.
</P>
<P>
The salt production target for the fiscal 1996-97 was fixed at
800,000 metric tons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bangladesh's total demand for salt is 780,000 metric
tons. Of the total, 612,000 tons goes for human consumption,
55,000 tons for livestock and fish cultivation and 113,000 tons
for industrial raw materials and other purposes.
</P>
<P>
A total of 43,000 acres of land has so far come under salt
cultivation under the direct patronization of the state-owned
BSCIC.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
