<HEADLINE> French Parties Start Campaign, Socialist Win Not Excluded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- As France's ruling majority parties
and the opposition Socialist Party have kicked off their campaign
for the legislative elections scheduled for May 25 and June 1,
observers do not exclude a possible victory by the Socialists.
</P>
<P>
Lionel Jospin, first secretary of the Socialist Party, today
turned down an invitation by the French Television One to have a
four-party debate with Prime Minister Alain Juppe, who is the
president of the ruling Gaullist Rally for the Republic (RPR),
Francois Leotard, head of RPR's ally of the Union for French
Democracy (UDF), and the national secretary of the Communist Party,
Robert Hue.
</P>
<P>
Jospin said he prefers a face-to-face debate with Juppe in
order to convey a clear message to the French people.
</P>
<P>
When starting his legislative campaign Thursday evening, the
Socialist leader described the balance sheet of the government
over the past two years as "a patent failure."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Juppe said Thursday evening during his campaign tour
in Marseille that the Socialist Party is a party which "mistakes
the century."
</P>
<P>
However, a close friend of President Jacques Chirac today
warned that the opposition Socialists could score a victory in the
elections, because of the strong opposition by the people to the
government's policy of launching the Euro "at all costs."
</P>
<P>
Writer Denis Tillinac told the daily Parisien today that one
should not "under-estimate" Jospin, who he said "is a very
valuable man" and understands "the fatal risk of Euro at all
costs."
</P>
<P>
He also warned that if the French people feel that the
dissolution of parliament by President Chirac is only a "political
maneuver" aimed at securing the launching of the Euro, the ruling
majority will lose the elections.
</P>
<P>
Also today, a poll by the CSA polling institute published in Le
Nouvel Economiste showed that a majority of French people think
that Chirac has "renounced" the promises he made during the 1995
presidential election campaign in salary raise, employment and
health spending.
</P>
<P>
But a poll by the IPSOS institute published on Thursday said
that the ruling majority will maintain 292 seats in the 577-seat
National Assembly (parliament), where the absolute majority is 289
seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
