<HEADLINE> ADB to Help Pakistan Establish Debt Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) will provide a loan of 300 million US dollar to the
Pakistani government for creating a long-term debt market as well
as a secondary market in the country.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with the Federation of Pakistan Chambers of
Commerce and Industry today in Karachi, Sadiq Zaidi, an ADB
representative, said the main cause of slow industrial progress in
Pakistan is absence of long-term credit policy.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to introduce capital market reforms in
Pakistan," he was quoted by the Associated Press of Pakistan as
saying, adding that "ADB is trying to create a long-term debt
market to cater to the needs of local industry."
</P>
<P>
Investment schemes are not successful in Pakistan as the
country lacks a secondary market, he said. Many projects, started
with private investment, were gravely affected due to
non-availability of a secondary market, said Zaidi.
</P>
<P>
"We are advocating to create a secondary market so that the
development projects, for which investments are raised, may not be
affected," Zaidi added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
