<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Immunize Children Among "Floating" People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China, observing National
Immunization Day, launched a nationwide campaign today to immunize
children who were not vaccinated against infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
Medical workers across the country will deliver oral polio
vaccine to unvaccinated children under the age seven, or give them
injections of pertussis, diphtheria, tetanus, and measles
vaccines, throughout the week to come.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will mainly target children among the migrant or
"floating" people, children whose births are not included in the
family planning quota, and those live in remote and poor areas,
according to Zhou Jun, an official with the Ministry of Public
Health.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ministry of Public Health and Beijing
municipal government, and representatives of the World Health
Organization and UNICEF participated in the vaccination activity
which was held in Huaxiang Town in Beijing's southern outskirts
today.
</P>
<P>
Local medics of the town, where many transient people live,
provided vaccines to children and handed out materials to spread
knowledge of immunization.
</P>
<P>
"We felt the urgency to conduct the vaccination program among
these children because they may become a potential risk to cause
outbreak of some infectious diseases," said Yin Dakui,
vice-minister of public health.
</P>
<P>
Low immunization coverage rate in some areas has led to rising
incidence of measles, and even a measles epidemic there, he said.
</P>
<P>
Trends of migration from rural to urban areas in recent years
have brought many Chinese away from their hometowns, and also the
shelter of local health care and immunization system.
</P>
<P>
Due to lack of awareness and other reasons, many young parents
among the floating people have no idea about whether or how to
immunize their children.
</P>
<P>
Some parents who have violated the family planning policy and
have more children often withhold facts about those children,
including their health data. Thus many children have no access to
prompt vaccination.
</P>
<P>
"We've urged local authorities responsible for immunization to
discover unvaccinated children and to immunize them," Zhou Jun
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
