<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDI Center Goes into Operation in Tianjin Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- An EDI (electronic data
interchange) Center went into operation today in Tianjin in north
China, making it the first port in China to be equipped with an
EDI system for international cargo container transport.
</P>
<P>
The center provides 24-hour graph and file transmission and
information-saving services, as well as bulletins for regular
cargo container shipping services, and import information.
</P>
<P>
Enabling data to be shared among department, industries,
regions and countries, the center will greatly alleviate port
congestion caused by delayed information, and improve the
efficiency of container traffic at the port.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin port invested a total of 10.07 million yuan (1.21
million US dollars) in setting up the center, which uses software
imported from Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Electronic information transmission and operation systems are a
main part of China's endeavor to promote technological progress
and management modernization for international cargo container
transport at its ports.
</P>
<P>
China plans to expand transmission of electronic information to
four main ports of entry and 120 related units, and deal with 80
percent of container transport files by way of EDI. 
</P>
</TEXT>
