<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Welcomes South Africa's Accession to Lome Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- South Africa would bring new
strength and dynamism to the Lome Convention between the European
Union (EU) and African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) countries, a
senior EU official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Joao de Deus Pinheiro, EU commissioner responsible for
relations with ACP countries, made the comment in Luxembourg after
the EU and ACP countries had agreed on the terms for South
Africa's membership of the Lome Convention.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner congratulated the people and the government of
South Africa who "brought their country from isolation right into
the heart of ACP-EU family of states."
</P>
<P>
It was an event of "historical significance," he said, adding
that the Convention finally included all of sub-Saharan Africa 22
years after the signing of the first Lome Convention.
</P>
<P>
Pinheiro also praised South Africa for its values of tolerance,
peace and multiculturalism, which he said were precisely the
source of the Lome Convention's commitments and its overarching
objective.
</P>
<P>
The Lome Convention lays down the political relations between
the 15 EU member states and the 70 ACP countries, most of which are
former colonies of European countries. It also regulates relations
in the area of trade and aid.
</P>
<P>
The Convention is founded on three principles -- partnership,
contracts and a combination of fields of cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
