<HEADLINE> Aids Relief Food Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Sitosterol, a kind of food in
South Africa, is found to be able to prolong the lifespan of
aids-infected cats, the Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
Professor Patric Boiue of Stellenbosch University, South Africa,
said tests on the cats infected with Hiv virus that causes Aids
indicated that those which take sitosterol survived their contrasts
which did not take the food by 57 to 125 weeks.
</P>
<P>
The same thing is expected on humans, he was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that patients who have been on trial of the food for
the past five years are doing well.
</P>
<P>
The professor claimed their research shows the food is also
usefull in fighting against arthritis, sclerosis and tuberculosis.
enditem

