<HEADLINE> Consultations Over Zaire Peace Talks Continue in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- South African negotiators are
consulting a wide range of roleplayers in Africa and elsewhere on
arrangements for the long-awaited direct talks between Zairean
President Mobutu Sese Seko and rebel leader Laurent Kabila, an
informed source said here today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Ministry spokesman Pieter Swanepoel was quoted as
saying in Cape Town that consultations with interested roleplayers
continued, but he declined to give details of the issue, said the
source.
</P>
<P>
President Nelson Mandela last week extended a formal invitation to
Mobutu, offering to host the first ever face-to-face talks between
Mobutu and Kabila in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, Mobutu wanted a new venue closer to Zaire because he could
not travel to South Africa for the talks due to his ill health.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Special Envoy to Zaire and the Great Lakes region,
Mohamed Sahnoun, held discussions with South African Deputy President
Thabo Mbeki in Pretoria on Thursday over the timing and venue of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun refused to expand on his talks with Mbeki, but adding
negotiators were "still working" on when and where the proposed peace
talks should be held.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel said Sahnoun had also spoken by phone earlier today to
Deputy Foreign Affairs Minister Aziz Pahad, who was travelling from
Cape Town to Pretoria this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Subtantial consultations had also been held over the statement by
the United Nations Security Council this morning expressing alarm over
reports of massacres and other human rights violations in the
rebel-controlled eastern Zaire where thousands of malnourished Rwandan
refugees are currently camped. enditem

