<HEADLINE> China's Economic Zones Maintain Stable Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China's five special economic
zones (SEZ) have reported stable expansion of economy in 1996,
according to an ongoing conference on the development of SEZs.
</P>
<P>
The five economic zones of Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Xiamen, Shantou
and Hainan scored 215.5 billion yuan (25.96 billion US dollars) of
gross domestic production last year, up 14.3 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
Their GDP increase was five percentage points more than the
national level, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Pudong New Area reported 51.02 billion yuan of GDP
last year, representing an increase of 22.8 percent over the year
before. 
