<HEADLINE> EU Executive Arm Proposes Anti-Dumping Duties on Cotton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive arm of the European Union (EU), today proposed to impose
definitive anti-dumping duties on imports of grey cotton fabric.
</P>
<P>
The proposed punitive measure will cover EU member states'
imports from India, Pakistan, Indonesia, Turkey, Egypt and China.
</P>
<P>
The Commission's move was made after an in-depth investigation
into the possible impact of the anti-dumping duties on European
producers and users of cotton fabric.
</P>
<P>
The probe allegedly confirmed that cut-price imports have
caused European competitors to suffer a decline in sales, strong
downward pressure on prices and financial losses.
</P>
<P>
But officials lowered the dumping margin from 19 percent
to an average of some 15 percent and, citing the specific nature
and use of medical gauze, excluded the product from the duties.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the latest move, the European Commission decided last
November to impose provisional anti-dumping duties on imported
cotton fabric for a period of six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
