<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Mortgage Lending Slows Down in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's new mortgage
lending continued to slow down in March, according to the results
of the latest monthly survey conducted by the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA).
</P>
<P>
Gross new loans made during the month fell by 10.6 percent to
16.8 billion HK dollars (2.15 billion U.S. dollars), compared with
 a drop of 8.9 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
The fall in gross loans made, coupled with a rise in repayment
of loans in the month, resulted in a slower rate of growth of
outstanding mortgage loans, which was 1.6 percent in March
compared with 2.7 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
The average rate of growth of outstanding loans in the three
months to March also decreased to 30.1 percent from 34.3 percent
in the three months to February.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, new loans approved during the month rose by
17 percent to 21.1 billion HK dollars (2.71 billion U.S. dollars),
 in line with the revival of primary market activity in March.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chief Executive of the HKMA David Carse said, "The
slower pace of new mortgage lending in March was a reflection of
seasonal factors in February. Loan demand accelerated again in
March as more new properties were put up for sale, but there are
indications that market conditions have since cooled."  
</P>
</TEXT>
