<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Rejects Israeli Request for Diplomatic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has turned down
repeated request by Israel for diplomatic ties as it is not
satisfied with the latter's attitude toward Palestine, Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad said today.
</P>
<P>
"We've said it that we shall not have diplomatic ties with them
until they honor their agreement not to be hostile to the
Palestinians," he said during a question and answer session at a
symposium in Petaling Jaya adjacent to the capital city on "The
Islamic World and Global Cooperation: Preparing for the 21st
Century" which he opened earlier.
</P>
<P>
Israel has not given freedom to Palestine and "because of this
we don't want to have diplomatic ties with them," Mahathir said
when asked to clarify Malaysia's stand on ties with Israel in the
light of an Israeli team taking part in a recent international
cricket tournament here.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir acknowledged that the presence of the Israeli
cricketers triggered public anger at the government although the
idea behind allowing them here was to open the eyes of the
Israelis to Islam's virtues upheld in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He said it was never the intention to do something that would
put the Muslims at a disadvantage or to defeat the purpose of the
Palestinian struggle.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Malaysia has supported the Palestinian cause more
than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
"We shall not betray the Islamic struggle, but fighting for a
cause does not simply mean exchanging gunfire. There are other
ways of doing it, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 participants, including politicians, academicians,
corporate leaders, government officials and journalists are
attending the three-day symposium jointly organized by the Oxford
Center for Islamic Studies and the Institute of Islamic
Understanding in Malaysia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
