<P>
CAIRO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa has disclosed that today's talks between Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and visiting President of Uganda Yoweri
Museveni dealt with bilateral relations and the situation in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters here that the talks dealt with two main
issues, namely relations between Egypt and Uganda and the steady
rise in cooperation, particularly in the private sector whether
in the agricultural, industrial or energy fields, and, secondly,
the situation in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Joint investments in the two countries have reached millions
of U.S. dollars, he said, adding that talks will take place today
between the Ugandan president and Egyptian Deputy Premier and
Minister of Agriculture and Land Reclamation Youssef Wali to
intensify cooperation in the field of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Museveni arrived here this morning on a two-day visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also disclosed that he will be flying to Uganda next
week for further talks and consultation both on bilateral
relations and on issues relating to the situation in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question whether his talks in Kampala next week
will deal with the establishment of a joint industrial zone,
Moussa said he will be accompanied during the visit to Uganda by
a group of businessmen.
</P>
<P>
He said that talks were already underway for the establishment
of agricultural, industrial and trading zones with joint
investments from the two countries. 
</P>
