<HEADLINE> Singapore Man Fined Heavily for Cigarettes Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A 42-year-old unemployed
Singapore man was fined 9.2 million Singapore dollars, or about
6.4 million U.S. dollars at the current exchange rate, for
smuggling in more than two tons of cigarettes, local television
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The fine handed out to Fong Weng Liong, the smuggler, was
believed to be the heaviest ever meted out and the man also
received a two-year jail sentence.
</P>
<P>
In addition, if he is unable to pay the fine, Fong will have to
serve another 63 months and 20 days' imprisonment in default, the
television report said.
</P>
<P>
Fong admitted to 22 charges relating to duty-unpaid cigarettes
while his accomplice Subramani Munusamy pleaded guilty to 16
similar charges. Together they had brought in more than 430,000
Singapore dollars' (about 298,600 U.S. dollars) worth of
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
The offense took place between February and April this year at
the Keppel Shipyard in the southern part of the Singapore island
where they bribed three security officers to allow the goods to be
unloaded.
</P>
<P>
The guards -- Krishna Kandasamy, Benedict Soosai and Bidin
Hussain -- were also convicted of smuggling. Krishna must pay a
fine of more than 3.7 million Singapore dollars (about 2.57
million U.S. dollars) or serve 45 months in jail. Meanwhile, Bidin
will have to spend 53 months in jail if he cannot pay his fine of
4.3 million Singapore dollars (about 2.99 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
