<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment in China's Inland Areas Encouraged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Overseas business people are
encouraged to invest in central and western China, Sun Zhenyu,
vice-minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation, said
today.
</P>
<P>
"In the future, while expanding foreign capital utilization in
the coastal regions, the Chinese government will increase its
investment in the central and western parts and will encourage and
actively promote foreign businesses to make investment in those
areas," Sun said at an international seminar on China's economic
reform and the liberalization of its accounting market.
</P>
<P>
He added that China's preferential policies toward the east and
coastal areas since the start of the economic reform and
opening-up drive in the late 1970s have been successful.
</P>
<P>
It is an important objective in China's strategy of economic
growth to gradually narrow the gap in economic development between
coastal regions and the central and western areas, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
China's efforts to deepen reform and the new situation brought
about by the economic development over the years have created new
opportunities for central and western China to open wider to the
rest of the world and to utilize more foreign investment, he told
participants of the seminar, which was co-sponsored by the Chinese
Institute of Certified Public Accountants and the Hong Kong
Society of Accountants.
</P>
<P>
Projects which can fully exploit the advantages of the central
and western areas in human and natural resources and which are in
line with the state industrial policy have been listed as areas
encouraged for foreign investment, according to Sun.
</P>
<P>
He also said that restrictions on the projects limited for
foreign investment can be eased to a proper extent if the projects
can truly exploit the resource advantages of these regions and
they conform with the state industrial policies.
</P>
<P>
In yet another move to encourage overseas investment in central
and western China, the State Council in September 1996 granted
inland authorities more power, raising the amount of foreign
investment involved in each project which the authorities of the
inland provinces, cities, and autonomous regions can approve from
10 million US dollars to 30 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The measures taken will help simplify the procedure to approve
overseas-funded enterprises and thereby enable the inland areas to
attract more overseas capital, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China altogether approved the
establishment of 283,800 overseas-funded enterprises between 1979
and 1996, with contractual overseas investment totaling nearly 470
billion dollars. The amount actually utilized stood at 176.59
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
China has been the largest destination of foreign investment
among all developing countries since 1993, statistics show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
