<HEADLINE> Albanian FM Sees Little Chance for Monarchy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Foreign Minister Arjan
Starova said here today that he did not regard restoration of a
monarchy in Albania as likely.
</P>
<P>
"There is a very slight possibility for that, but I don't think
such a choice will be made," Starova said after talks with his
German counterpart Klaus Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
The call for restoring a monarchy, and for a referendum to this
regard, was made by the exiled son of former Albanian king Zogu I,
Leka Zogu, during a recent visit to Albania.
</P>
<P>
However, Starova hoped the elections in Albania will go ahead
as scheduled on June 29, and said the preconditions for that would
be the end of chaos and restoration of public order in the country.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also stressed the needs for the
6,000-strong foreign troops now being deployed in Albania as part
of the eight-nation protection force to stay there until elections
were held.
</P>
<P>
"If the elections were postponed, which I don't think is
likely, of course, the multinational force would need a second
mandate because they are due to stay there for three months," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
