<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Further Liberalize Accounting Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to liberalize
its accounting services step by step, a senior accountant said
today.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome all international accounting firms and foreign CPA
(certified public accountant) firms to do business in China. We
also welcome our fellow accountants in Hong Kong, Taiwan, and
Macao to the mainland to seek business opportunities," Ding
Pingzhun, secretary general of the Chinese Institute of Certified
Public Accountants (CICPA), said today at an international seminar
on China's economic reform and the opening of its accountancy
market.
</P>
<P>
Ding said that China has opened its accounting services for a
long time. He noted that while opening up wider the accounting
market, the Chinese government is gradually improving the
regulation of the overseas accounting firms entering China.
</P>
<P>
"As in all other countries, the opening up of the Chinese
accounting market is not unconditional or without limitation,"
Ding told the seminar, which was co-sponsored by the CICPA and the
Hong Kong Society of Accountants.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese rules and regulations, qualified overseas
accounting firms can open representative offices or form joint
venture CPA firms in China. They are also permitted to recruit
member firms in China.
</P>
<P>
China's national unified CPA test was opened to overseas
applicants in 1994. To date, over 4,000 people from 12 countries
and regions have applied for the test.
</P>
<P>
So far, 14 overseas accounting agencies have opened 28
representative offices in Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, and a
number of other Chinese cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
