<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Laws Encourage Economic Growth in China's Ethnic Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The increase in the number of
local laws on politics, the economy, culture, and social life in
ethnic areas of China has helped economic growth and unity among
various ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
Autonomous prefectures and autonomous counties have adopted 123
laws since 1980, and another 113 specific regulations and 59 law
modifications or supplementary regulations have been passed.
</P>
<P>
The Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region made 26 local laws in
1996, half of which deal with the economy. They include
agricultural technology, administration of state-owned farms, and
auditing collective groups in rural and pasture areas.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the total grain output of Inner Mongolia came to 15.35
billion kilograms, 4.8 billion kilograms more than that of 1995,
which put Inner Mongolia at the top place in the country in per
capita grain output.
</P>
<P>
In the Ningxia Autonomous Region, the people's congress drafted
land administration, environmental protection, and contract system
laws for rural areas. These measures helped local economic
growth. In 1996, the GDP in Ningxia was 19.4 billion yuan (2.4
billion dollars), 10.5 percent more than for 1995.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that economic development is not obtained at the
expense of the environment, many ethnic areas have drawn up
environmental protection laws.
</P>
<P>
The Tibet Autonomous Region made a series of regulations on
forest and wild animal protection, and on grassland, water
resources, and mining administration.
</P>
<P>
China has also developed a 2.4-million-strong team of cadres
from ethnic areas to help with the legislation. Special
regulations in ethnic areas have also helped increase the number
of school-age children in school. The rate in Inner Mongolia and
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has risen to 98.5 percent, one
percentage point higher than the country's average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
