<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Advance Reform of Accounting Profession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Accelerating reforms of the
accounting profession has become an important task facing the
whole nation in order to facilitate the standardized development
of Chinese securities market, a senior securities official said
today.
</P>
<P>
"To improve the technical and ethical standards of Chinese
accountants is the key to coordinating business reform and to
facilitating the development of the Chinese securities market,"
said Li Jiange, vice chairman of the China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC), at an international seminar on accountancy.
</P>
<P>
The securities industry watchdog will improve the disclosure
system of listed companies, keep a tighter control over certified
public accountants and domestic and overseas accountanting firms
engaged in the securities sector, according to the vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
All these measures are aimed at fostering a team of Certified
Public Accountants (CPAs) of high calibre and ethical level,
making it a backbone force in a standardized and sustained
development of the securities market, noted Li.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, CPA's, in order to stay in the securities business
required special certification that was acquired only by taking a
national examination given by the CSRC and the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The CSRC and Ministry of Finance also conducted annual
check-ups of CPAs and accounting firms and imposed harsh penalties
on rule-breakers.
</P>
<P>
The accounting profession and the securities market have been
two interacting forces since the market took shape in 1991. As the
expansion of the securities market gained speed in 1992, China
made its first try to reform its accounting rules by promulgating
the "Accountanting Standards for Business Enterprises" and
"Accounting Regulations for Incorporated Business Enterprises,"
said Li.
</P>
<P>
Enhanced cooperation between the Chinese and overseas
securities regulators also made the accounting system in China
converge with international norms, and made it possible to assess
the performance of Chinese enterprises with international
accounting standards, thereby paving the way for Chinese
enterprises to be listed overseas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
