<HEADLINE> S. Korean President's Son Denies Allegations on Hanbo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Kim Hyun-chul, son of South Korean
President Kim Young-sam, denied today taking bribes from the
collapsed Hanbo Group or committing any irregularities interfering
in state affairs.
</P>
<P>
During a testimony at the National Assembly where he served as
a witness, the 38-year-old junior Kim apologized to the people and
his father for causing public stir, saying "it's all because I did
not think or act properly."
</P>
<P>
However, except admitting to recommending certain people to his
father for government posts, he denied other public accusations
and his role behind massive bank loan arrangements for Hanbo and
systematic meddling in all personnel appointments.
</P>
<P>
"I will accept punishment if I am guilty of a crime. Legal
matters will be up to the prosecution," Kim said.
</P>
<P>
He has been suspected of playing a leading role in brokering
huge bank loans for the now bankrupt Hanbo, taking 225 million
U.S. dollars in rebate in Hanbo's business contracts, and
interfering in ruling camp nominations for general elections and
government appointments.
</P>
<P>
The junior Kim's testimony is the highlight of the three-week
parliamentary hearing summoned to investigate the explosive Hanbo
graft scandal.
</P>
<P>
Kim was investigated in February for his alleged connections
with Hanbo, but prosecutors cleared his name citing lack of
evidence.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Kim publicly apologized for the bribery
scandal and promised to keep his controversial son away from
politics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
