<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The new non-racial and
unified Kwazulu/Natal Agricultural Union would make a positive
contribution to reconciliation and reconstruction, President
Nelson Mandela said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the launching ceremony in Pietermaritzburg, Mandela said
the new union was of the great importance. It reflected and
promoted de-racializing agriculture and society in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The union joins the former Black Natal Agricultural Union, the
National African Farmers' Union, the South Coast Indian Farmers'
Association and the mainly White Kwazulu/Natal Farmers' Union.
</P>
<P>
It would help overcome historical divisions and would create
the possibility for all farmers to work together to eliminate the
inequalities of the past, a source said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela hoped this sign of growing cooperation between large
and small-scale farmers, following the formation of a similar
union in Eastern Cape Province, would be echoed elsewhere in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Minister and Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP) leader
Mangosuthu Buthelezi said at the ceremony the new union would
bring together farmers from all races in the IFP-controlled
Province.
</P>
<P>
"The importance of this achievement cannot be over-emphasized,
as one cannot overstate the enormity of the challenges with which
your union is confronted," said Buthelezi. 
</P>
