<HEADLINE> HK Retail Sales Rise in First Two Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's total retail sales
decreased in value and volume in February, but increased for the
first two months.
</P>
<P>
The value of total retail sales in Hong Kong in February was
estimated at 17.9 billion HK dollars (2.3 billion U.S. dollars),
a decrease of 3 percent compared with February 1996, according to
the provisional figures on retail sales released by the Census and
 Statistics Department today.
</P>
<P>
The total retail sales decreased 7 percent in volume after
discounting the effect of price changes over the period.
</P>
<P>
But in the first two moths of 1997 total retail sales rose 7
percent in value and 3 percent in volume compared with the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Among different types of commodities, sales of motor vehicles
rose most significantly, by 38 percent in both value and volume
terms in the first two months this year over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Sales of miscellaneous consumer goods and valuable goods,
including jewelry, watches and clocks and valuable gifts, also
recorded notable growth of 12 and 6 percent in value respectively.
 In terms of volume, they increased 7 and 10 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Sales of commodities in supermarkets, food, alcoholic drinks
and tobacco and other consumer durable goods also registered
increases, by 6, 3 and 2 percent in value respectively, but all
remained virtually no change in volume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
