<HEADLINE> Deregulation of Telecom Sector Urged for West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of communications in
English-speaking western African countries have called on their
governments to deregulate the sector so as to boost its
development in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
A communique was issued at the end of a three-day workshop on
Internet in the Nigerian capital of Abuja on Thursday saying that
only the deregulation of the sector would guarantee the sector's
viability in the region and in sub-Sahara Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministers, the deregulation of the
communications sector would stimulate growth and provide new
opportunities in education, trade, health care, job creation,
food security and economic integration.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also adopted what they termed the "African
Information Society Initiative", an action framework to build the
continent's information and communication infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
They recommended that governments should develop a framework
and mechanism to ensure the participation of all sectors in
coordinating and harmonizing the multiple efforts of the private
sector, non-governmental organizations and the media.
</P>
<P>
They suggested the establishment of a strong, independent
regulatory body to regulate the telecommunication sector,
membership of which should include delegates from government and
associations of industry, labor, academic, private and consumer.
</P>
<P>
The communique was signed by communications ministers from
Gambia, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Ghana and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was organized by the U.N. Development Program in
collaboration with the Nigerian Ministry of Communications and
its parastatals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
