<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Executive Council Members Declare Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Executive
Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR)
have completed their declarations of interests which are now
available for public inspection upon request, a spokesman of the
HKSAR Chief Executive's Office said here today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said a system of declaration of interests for
members of the Executive Council has been worked out with
reference to the current arrangements for Executive and
Legislative Councilors and senior government officials.
</P>
<P>
He said it has stricken a fine balance between the
accountability of the Executive Council and the members' right to
privacy.
</P>
<P>
The scope of declarable items for the members of the Executive
Council of the HKSAR is broadly similar to that under the existing
system. However, the members are required to make known the land
and property they own both locally and outside Hong Kong,
irrespective of their value and whether or not they are used for
self-occupation, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The members' investment activities in Hong Kong securities and
futures as well as in shareholdings of overseas companies which
carry out business activities in Hong Kong will be make known to
the chief executive on a confidential basis but will not be made
public, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currency transactions involving the Hong Kong dollar of a value
of over 200,000 HK dollars are an additional item to be reported
confidentially, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that in declaring land, property and
financial interests, the members should include those which are
held in the name of their spouse, children, other persons or
companies but are actually owned by themselves or in which they
have a beneficial interest.
</P>
<P>
Under Article 47 of the Basic Law, on assuming office, the
chief executive is required to make known his assets to the chief
justice of the Court of Final Appeal. Tung Chee Hwa will make the
declarations again on July 1, 1997, when he is sworn in as the
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the declarations of interests, the members of
the HKSAR Executive Council are required to declare, also in an
open register, financial sponsorships they receive or overseas
sponsored visits they make as well as gifts worth over 2,000 HK
dollars to them or their spouses other than those given by their
relatives or on special occasions.
</P>
<P>
The sources of any gifts received will be kept confidential and
reported to the chief executive only, so as to protect the privacy
of the third party, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive has decided to declare publicly any gifts
presented to him during his tenure as the chief executive
irrespective of value, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gifts with commercial value will be disposed of through the
Treasury after July 1, 1997, and the proceeds will be donated to
charitable organizations.
</P>
<P>
As regards items which Tung would like to retain, valuations
will be obtained from the Treasury and Tung will purchase them.
The proceeds will again be donated to charities, the spokesman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
