<HEADLINE> South Korea's Exports Expected to Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's exports are expected
to rebound rapidly from its long setbacks as prices of its key
export items have recovered, the Finance and Economy Ministry said
today.
</P>
<P>
The optimistic forecast based on the recovering price of
petrochemical and steel products, semiconductors and other key
items, the Yohap News Agency quoted a ministry official as saying.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the nation's invisible trade deficit narrowed last
month, and the current-account imbalance also showed rapid
improvement.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the value of the Japanese yen is expected to rebound
against the U.S. dollar. The revaluation will offer good
opportunities to South Korea, which has a similar export structure
to Japan, to increase its exports.
</P>
<P>
Both Japan and the United States reportedly think it
disadvantageous to its economy to let the current exchange rate
remain for a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar has recently been moving in the range between
125 yen and 126 yen.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's current-account deficit in February was 2.45
billion U.S. dollars, down from 3.14 billion dollars in
January. The figure in March is expected to be below 2 billion
dollars and that of April will be even lower, said ministry
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
