<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Peace Process Stands Still in Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The peace process in the southern
Philippines has run into another stalemate with the third round of
preliminary peace talks between the government and a major Muslim
rebel group having ended Thursday without any substantive
progress.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting in Catobato city in western
Mindanao, negotiators from the government and the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) failed to touch upon issues regarding a
wider truce in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The two sides had planned to discuss the conditions to be
provided by both sides for a comprehensive cease-fire covering the
entire Mindanao region to ensure that the on-going peace talks
would not be derailed by sporadic fighting between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The just-concluded low-level peace talks, initially scheduled
to open on April 9, had been postponed twice because of renewed
exchange of shelling between the government troops and MILF rebels
in Buldon town, Maguindanao Province, early this month.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the technical committees of both sides only
agreed to continue implementing an interim cease-fire in Buldon,
signed this January, to prevent an escalation of tension there.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to leave the issue of extending this local truce to
other areas of Mindanao to the next meeting, which will be held in
early May.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also failed to put an end to their row over which
side should be responsible for the March 16 Buldon bomb attack at
a school, which killed 10 students and one teacher.
</P>
<P>
The MILF has demanded that the government look into the
incident, for which it said the military should be blamed. But the
military has bluntly denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said there is a long way to go for Manila and the
MILF to start formal peace talks since the two sides, which began
their first-ever preliminary talks in January, have so far been
wide apart on the conditions for the cessation of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Ghazali Gaafar, chairman of the MILF's peace panel, said
earlier this week that unless both sides forge an expanded truce,
no formal negotiations could take off.
</P>
<P>
During the second round of initial talks with the government in
February, the MILF presented four conditions for ending
hostilities between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
These conditions include the military's adherence to the
Articles of War of the Geneva Convention, a halt to troop
deployment in Mindanao, recognition of MILF-held territories and
the immediate pullout of troops near MILF camps.
</P>
<P>
The government has not formally replied to these conditions and
so far failed to provide its own stance for a comprehensive
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
But Armed Forces Chief of Staff Gen. Arnulfo Acedara earlier
made it clear that the government can not regard MILF-controlled
areas as separate territory and refused to pull out troops
deployed near MILF bastions.
</P>
<P>
Despite the reopening of the peace talks, tension remains high
in the towns of Buldon, Sirawai and Carmen, where the government
and MILF fighters have faced a standoff during recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Col. Rodolfo Garcia, head of the 603rd Infantry Brigade based
in Buldon, said the situation in this town of 25,000 remains
volatile and armed conflicts may flare up at any time between MILF
rebels and government troops.
</P>
<P>
In Sirawai town, Zamboanga del Norte Province, government
troops continued their pursuit of fleeing MILF elements after
capturing a major MILF camp in the town. Clashes between
government troops and the MILF in Sirawai have claimed at least 35
lives in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The government has sought to sign a peace deal with the MILF to
end scattered incidents of rebellion in the interest of economic
development in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Economy in the southern Philippines has long lagged behind the
other parts of the country. Mindanao is rich in natural resources
but has long been neglected due to the decades-old separatist
Muslim movement there.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway group of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF), is currently the largest anti-government
force in the country, with an estimated membership of 12,000.
</P>
<P>
The government signed a peace deal with the MNLF last
September, ending nearly three decades of war between the MNLF and
the government troops in the south. But the peace accord was
rejected by the MILF.  
</P>
</TEXT>
