<HEADLINE> Nepali Parties to Protest Commission's Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Small political parties in
Nepal will take to the streets to protest the Election
Commission's decision not to allow them to use their own symbols
for next month's local elections, sources here said today.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the 17 parties decided at a Thursday meeting to
launch a legal and street struggle against the decision, according
to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Under their protest program, the parties will organize a mass
rally in front of the compound of the Election Commission on
Sunday and call a nationwide general strike next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission Thursday decided to allow four national
parties, including the three ruling partners and the main
opposition party, to use their party symbols in the local
elections to be held next month.
</P>
<P>
But the commission also decided that candidates of small
parties, which won less than 3 percent of the total votes in last
elections, could only use symbols allocated by the commission.
</P>
<P>
Nepali voters will elect leaders of about 4,000 local
administration bodies throughout the country at village,
municipality and district levels beginning May 17.  
</P>
</TEXT>
