<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian state budget includes further raises in
wages to approximately double the inflation rate, Minister of
Finance Mohieddin el-Ghareb told a parliamentary session recently.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government is keen on achieving a balance
between wages and prices, adding that debt increases should not be
a concern because part of the privatization proceeds will be
allocated for paying back accumulated interest.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that the government makes amendments
to the balance sheet only when the need arises, the Egyptian Al
Ahram weekly reported today.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The World Bank (WB) will take part in a giant project
to develop Egypt's western desert into a new industrial and
agricultural community.
</P>
<P>
A high-ranking WB delegation has arrived in Cairo to review the
bank's participation in conducting the studies and key research
for the New Valley project, the Egyptian Al Ahram weekly reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Another WB delegation comprising of agricultural research
experts and professors has been examining the possibility of
financing the project.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon recorded a growth rate of 5 percent in the
first quarter of 1997 compared with 3 percent in 1996, the Daily
Star, the only English daily in Beirut, today quoted the Lebanese
central bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The first quarter was positive and the main indicators show
good economic growth and inflation in Lebanese pounds under
control," said Riad Salame, governor of the Bank du Liban.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate stood at 9 percent in the first three
months this year.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate plunged to 3 percent in 1996 from 7 percent
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Salame said Thursday the surplus of 337 million U.S. dollars
in Lebanon's balance of payments in the first quarter was
"historic and encouraging" signs, which were accompanied by a
fall in interest rates on treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
A report published by the Lebanese Bankers' Association
Thursday also indicated improving economic conditions with a
sharp rise in construction activity and new business start-ups.
</P>
<P>
Banking performance also registered a slight improvement in
total lending in Lebanese pound, which increased by 1.3 percent
in the public sector and 1.55 percent in the private sector, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign currencies lending, however, dropped by 1.33
percent, suggesting lower interest rates were having a positive
impact on dollarization.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that exports of manufactured products
recorded a 19 percent drop between January and February, while
imports of machinery and equipment fell by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Volume of shares on the Beirut Stock Exchange rose by 36
percent in February, amounting to 1.8 million shares traded,
with total value of 22.3 million dollars compared to 16.4
million dollars in January.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A member of the Kuwaiti National Assembly said
today the parliament would soon issue a general legislation
specifying privatization policies in the country, according to the
official Kuwait News Agency (Kuna).
</P>
<P>
Abdel Wahab Al-Haroun, rapporteur of the parliamentary
Financial and Economic Affairs Committee, said that the proposed
legislation would comprehensively organize the privatization laws
in terms of securing public funds and national manpower rights and
supervising bodies planning to invest in projects and utilities to
be privatized.
</P>
<P>
He said the committee had already consulted the ministries of
finance, trade and industry, the Kuwait Investment Authority
(KIA), the Chamber of Commerce and Industry, as well as the
Kuwaiti Stock Exchanges and the Kuwaiti Economists Association on
the specifics of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's privatization plan starting in 1994 involves the
sale of public services and state holdings except the
state-owned oil sector which brings more than 80 percent of the
state revenues in the Gulf oil-rich state.
</P>
<P>
So far, Kuwait successfully implemented a program to sell the
state-owned stakes and shares to the private sector which,
Al-Haroun said, has helped in earning unprecedented revenues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
