<HEADLINE> Mozambican Customs to Be Administrated by British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican Customs will be
administrated by a British company called Crown Agents, which has
drafted a plan on over-all reforms in the Customs, from May, 1997
to 2000, local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The customs duties are estimated to increase by about 40
percent to 125 million U.S. Dollars at the end of this year over
1996 due to the move.
</P>
<P>
Under the three-year plan, the British firm will be in charge
of reorganizing the whole customs authorities, training personnel
there and revising all customs laws and operation regulations.
</P>
<P>
However, no staff will be fired with at least 100 to be
trained, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The plan is expected to cost about 35 million U.S. Dollars
from the British government and international donors.
</P>
<P>
The company won the administration rights of the Mozambican
Customs in an earlier governmental tender. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
