<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela: South Africa to Provide Syria with Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela has expressed his determination to provide Syria with arms
despite opposition from the U.S., today's Syrian newspaper Al
Thawra reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Mandela said in an interview with Kuwaiti
daily Al Qabas published Thursday that "we owe Syria a big debt
and we have to express our gratitude by providing it with arms
needed to defend itself."
</P>
<P>
The president further stated that "Syria is one of the few
countries that stood by our side in our struggle for liberation of
the apartheid rule in South Africa. We are now in a position to
reward it with something against whatever it has extended to us."
</P>
<P>
Mandela also stated that "had it not been the support of those
friendly countries, including Syria, we would never have been able
to attain what we have achieved in South Africa."
</P>
<P>
Washington had exerted great pressure on South Africa to compel
it to refrain from providing Syria with modern arms and technology.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had earlier affirmed that his country would sell arms
to Syria and would not submit to any threats.
</P>
<P>
But he revealed neither the volume of such arms nor their
kind and value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
