<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Commission Sceptical Over Easing British Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Commission of the European
Union (EU) has expressed deep doubt over British proposals on
relaxing a global ban on British beef exports, questioning the
reliability of the British program, the BBC television reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Britain's ruling Conservative government, lagging behind the
main opposition Labor party in all opinion polls in the run-up to
the May 1 general election, is desperate to achieve an early
lifting of the year-long beef ban to boost flagging Conservative
morale.
</P>
<P>
In February, the British government proposed to establish a
"certified herd scheme" to identify cows from BSE-free herds which
could then be exported.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Major last week appealed to his EU partners
to put an end to the beef trade embargo and he even dropped the
hint that he would sack his Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg if
he won the general election.
</P>
<P>
However, the BBC television reported that it had received a
copy of a letter which was written by two EU commissioners to Hogg
casting serious doubts over the British scheme.
</P>
<P>
EU Agriculture commissioner Franz Fischler and Consumer Affairs
Commissioner Emma Bonino questioned in the letter whether British
farmers' records could be trusted to prove that some cows were
BSE-free.
</P>
<P>
They also pointed out that a recently set-up central
computerized system of keeping track of healthy cows could not be
considered as reliable at this stage.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed a world-wide ban on British beef exports last
March when the British government admitted possible links between
mad cow disease and its human equivalent Creutzfeld-Jakob Disease.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission, the executive arm of the 15-nation bloc,
have repeatedly ruled out any early easing of the ban, saying more
veterinary inspections were needed to examine whether Britain had
complied fully with last year's Florence agreement which provided
a framework for a ban lifting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
