<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Listed as "Advanced Economy" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Washington-based
International Monetary Fund (IMF) recently classified Hong Kong as
an "advanced economy" along with the United States, Germany,
France and Japan and several other countries and regions, Hong
Kong Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The classification in the fund's latest World Economic Outlook
report is based on the fact that Hong Kong and the other four
places "share a number of important industrial economy
characteristics." The characteristics include per capita income
levels well within the range indicated by the group of industrial
economies, well-developed financial markets and diversified
economic structures with relatively large and rapidly growing
service sectors.
</P>
<P>
The report said the IMF dropped the "old industrial economy"
label to reflect the "declining share of employment in
manufacturing common to all the economies."
</P>
<P>
The same IMF report forecasts a 9.5-percent growth for China
this year, with inflation remaining at 6 percent and an economy
set for continued expansion.
</P>
<P>
It noted that given the inextricable links between Hong Kong
and China's mainland further growth for the territory in the years
ahead is beyond question.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
