<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Soldiers Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli Soldiers were
wounded in heavy exchanges of fire in south Lebanon early this
morning between Lebanese Muslim guerrillas on the one hand, and
Israeli forces and their South Lebanon Army (SLA) militia allies
on the other.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in south Lebanon said that Israeli artillery
fired more than 40 shells at vicinities of villages opposite the
Israeli self-proclaimed "security zone" in south Lebanon this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Gunmen of the Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of
God, directed their mortar shells and light weapons fire at
positions of the Israeli and SLA militia in the eastern and
central sectors of the occupied zone, the anonymous sources
said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the south Lebanon-based U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon (UNIFIL) said the two fighting sides traded fire over
Thursday night and the exchanges began to die down early this
morning.
</P>
<P>
He said he could not confirm reports that Katyusha rockets
were used by the guerrillas in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
SLA militia sources said guerrillas fired three salvoes of
rockets into the Israeli outposts of Marqaba and Blat deeply
inside the buffer zone at dawn, wounding two Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
This was the first casualties the Israeli occupation forces
in south Lebanon sustained since this month.
</P>
<P>
Two SLA militiamen were also lightly wounded and sent to
hospital in Marjauoun, the largest town in the
1,100-square-kilometer "security zone" carved by the Jewish state
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Three Lebanese civilians were wounded in Israeli helicopter
and artillery raids at a village on the edge of the occupied
zone Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Masoud, a police sergeant on leave, was wounded in
the shoulder and trader Daoud Idriss in the leg when two Israeli
helicopters strafed Kfar Tibnit at 1:15 p.m., one of the five
crossings between the border strip and the rest of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army sources in Jerusalem said the pair were injured
by a group of "terrorists" who fired machineguns and mortars at
Israeli positions in the buffer enclave. Israeli soldiers fired
back, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Ismail Doughman, 17. was also wounded in his right leg
in Kfar Tibnit by a bullet fired from the Israeli outpost of Ali
AI-Taher which overlooks the village.
</P>
<P>
The dawn clashes added to six died and 32 wounded the Israeli
casualties in south Lebanon since this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
