<HEADLINE> China Builds up First Simulated Underwater Lab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China's first lab to simulate
underwater environments has been recently constructed in Shanghai,
China's leading industrial coastal city.
</P>
<P>
The lab will focus research on sea rescue and salvage, wharf
building, development of marine resources, and maintenance of
underwater installations.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that only Germany and a few other developed
countries have such labs.
</P>
<P>
Divers can train in the lab, and astronauts can also train for
zero-gravity conditions.
</P>
<P>
The lab, with a total floor space of 2,930 square meters,
consists of a stagnant water pond, a running water pond, and an
experiment hall.
</P>
<P>
Built by the Underwater Engineering Institute attached to the
Ministry of Communications, the lab absorbed 14.7 million yuan
(1.83 million US dollars) of the cost.  
</P>
</TEXT>
