<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lip-Reading Helps Understanding of Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Watching a person's lips when he
speaks helps you to understand what he is saying, whether you can
hear him or not, according to the result of a brain scanner
experiment published today.
</P>
<P>
A team of British scientists using a brain scanner says
lip-reading activates the auditory cortex, the same brain region
that is involved in hearing.
</P>
<P>
The team became interested in how lip-reading helps us to
understand language after finding out that some deaf
schizophrenics "hear" voices when seeing a speaker mouthing at
them. That seemed to suggest that hearing and vision were linked
in some way.
</P>
<P>
Roots of the "hallucinations" may lie in the auditory cortex in
the light of studies of normal-hearing people reported in the
journal Science by Gemma Calvert, a psychologist from Oxford,
Prof. Tony David of the Institute of Psychiatry, and Prof. Ruth
Campbell of University College, London.
</P>
<P>
"This is an unexpected and intriguing finding, since this is
the first demonstration that visual information alone can activate
brain regions that are otherwise engaged by sound," Calvert said.
"Research provides a further illustration of how novel brain
imaging techniques can inform us about how the brain deals with
understanding speech." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament to Issue Legislation on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A member of the Kuwaiti
National Assembly said today the parliament would soon issue a
general legislation specifying privatization policies in the
country, according to the official Kuwait News Agency (Kuna).
</P>
<P>
Abdel Wahab Al-Haroun, rapporteur of the parliamentary
Financial and Economic Affairs Committee, said that the proposed
legislation would comprehensively organize the privatization laws
in terms of securing public funds and national manpower rights and
supervising bodies planning to invest in projects and utilities to
be privatized.
</P>
<P>
He said the committee had already consulted the ministries of
finance, trade and industry, the Kuwait Investment Authority
(KIA), the Chamber of Commerce and Industry, as well as the
Kuwaiti Stock Exchanges and the Kuwaiti Economists Association on
the specifics of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
The KIA has managed the government's privatization programs so
far.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's privatization plan starting in 1994 involves the
sale of public services and state holdings except the
state-owned oil sector which brings more than 80 percent of the
state revenues in the Gulf oil-rich state.
</P>
<P>
So far, Kuwait successfully implemented a program to sell the
state-owned stakes and shares to the private sector which,
Al-Haroun said, has helped in earning unprecedented revenues.
</P>
<P>
"State ownership in firms and sectors that are candidates for
privatization, apart from the oil sector, is estimated at 3.62
billion Kuwaiti dinars (11.95 billion U.S. dollars)," an
official of the Kuwaiti Finance Ministry told Xinhua earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
The official also said that since September 1994, the state
had sold shares worth over 700 million dinars (2.3 billion
dollars) in more than 20 local firms under the first phase of the
privatization program.
</P>
<P>
A draft law by the government to move to the next and more
controversial stage of privatizing heavily subsidized utility
firms, including water, electricity and telecommunications which
used to provide employment for Kuwaitis, was sent to parliament
last month.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Finance Minister Nasser Al-Rudhan said on April 4
that the Kuwaiti government temporarily put on hold the
privatization program to "avoid any negative consequences that
may result from privatization had the guarantees not been
taken."
</P>
<P>
Al-Haroun hoped to privatize all the government-owned
companies where the government has an absolute majority of shares
after legislating the privatization law which would secure rights
of the Kuwaiti manpower and monitor all privatization
transactions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti parliamentary Financial and Economic Affairs
Committee turned down, during a recent meeting, a draft law for
the set up of a Kuwaiti Telecommunication Company because the
parliament was intended to establish a general legislation
governing the privatization of public utilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
