<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200,000 Myanmar Refugees Return from Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- With a batch of 39 Rohingyas of
eight families returned to their home in Myanmar Thursday, a total
of 228,000 Myanmar Muslims have returned home from Bangladesh in
the last seven year, said officials in Cox's Bazar district
bordering Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
A quarter million Rohingyas left their home in the western
state of Arakan in Myanmar early 1991 and crossed into Bangladesh,
imposing a pressure on its socio-economic and ecological
condition.
</P>
<P>
However, nobody knows when the last refugee will get back to
his paternal property by crossing the Naaf River that flows
between Myanmar and Bangladesh, said the officials.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation began in August 1991 following a tripartite
agreement between Bangladesh, Myanmar and the United Nations High
Commission for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
At present, 21,916 refugees, living in two camps in Teknaf and
Ukhia of Cox's Bazar, are waiting for their repatriation.
</P>
<P>
Twenty other refugee camps at Ramu, Ukhia and Teknaf in Cox's
Bazar district and a part of Banadarban have been dismantled, said
 official sources.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka is now negotiating with Yangon for a fresh meeting of
senior officials of the two countries to bring an end to the
problem, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
