<HEADLINE> East China Province Opening up More to Overseas Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province,
one of the country's most developed areas, has had some good
results in opening up the local economy.
</P>
<P>
It is the third biggest foreign-trade base in China and did
about 4.35 billion US dollars worth of foreign trade in the first
quarter of this year alone, a nearly 51.5 percent rise over the
same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The local foreign trade is expected to help the province, which
is short of resources, increase its GDP by 12 percent and fixed
assets investment by 20 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The coastal province has more than 30,000 foreign-funded
enterprises, over half of which are operating and involved in
processing industry.
</P>
<P>
These have contributed a great deal to local economic growth,
doing more than 2.1 billion US dollars worth of foreign trade
during the first three months, double the figure for the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The province also intends to expand foreign technology
cooperation, and will send more laborers abroad for overseas
projects. During the first quarter, it signed 260 million US
dollars worth of contracts involving foreign technology.
</P>
<P>
The three-month period also saw approximately 200,000 overseas
visitors to the province, a 32 percent rise from the same period
of 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
