<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Put 600 Air-Conditioned Buses into Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China's largest economic center
will be able to face this summer a bit easier as 600
air-conditioned buses will be put into operation shortly in the
city proper.
</P>
<P>
Another 1,000 air-conditioned buses will be added by October 1,
China's National Day, giving public transportation in the
7.5-sq.km. downtown area a new look, the municipal Public
Utilities Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Conductors will also be wearing neater uniforms, providing more
standard service, and speaking more politely to meet Shanghai's
status as an international metropolis, the source said.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to upgrade another 1,000 buses in 1998, with no
changes in the routes, bus numbers, or timetable, the bureau told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 13,000 buses now travelling the more than
1,000 routes in Shanghai, handling 5.3 million passengers each
day, 7,000 of which operate in the city proper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
