<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebels to Resume Peace Talks in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Peace panels of the Philippine
government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) will meet
again on May 13-14 to discuss a comprehensive ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
This was decided by the two sides at the end of their third
round of low-level talks at a university in southern Mindanao. The
talks failed to produce any substantial result.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, said
today that the May talks will also hopefully break the impasse on
the issue of pulling back government and rebel troops in Buldon,
where thousands of soldiers and rebels are facing a standoff.
</P>
<P>
"Though the (recent) meeting was friendly and cordial, we were
not able to agree on the pull back of forces," Jaafar said.
</P>
<P>
Arnulfo Acedera, chief of staff of the Armed Forces of the
Philippines, said after a visit to Buldon Thursday that the
military has not yet implemented the four-kilometer pull back he
recommended.
</P>
<P>
"It will only start after a general ceasefire in Buldon and
other areas in Mindanao has been agreed and signed by both
panels," said Acedera who also explained his Buldon visit was in
no way related to the April 23-24 talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the government signed an interim truce in February
after a number of military clashes. However, the ceasefire
agreement was often violated with new fighting.
</P>
<P>
The MILF insists that a comprehensive ceasefire expanded to the
whole Mindanao should be reached before entering formal peace
talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
A breakaway group of the mainstream Moro National Liberation
Front which signed a peace agreement with the government last
year, the MILF is now the biggest rebel group in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
