<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 07:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Economic Growth Rate Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon recorded a growth rate
of 5 percent in the first quarter of 1997 compared with 3 percent
in 1996, the Daily Star, the only English daily in Beirut, today
quoted the Lebanese central bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The first quarter was positive and the main indicators show
good economic growth and inflation in Lebanese pounds under
control," said Riad Salame, governor of the Bank du Liban.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate stood at 9 percent in the first three
months this year.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate plunged to 3 percent in 1996 from 7 percent
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Salame said Thursday the surplus of 337 million U.S. dollars
in Lebanon's balance of payments in the first quarter was
"historic and encouraging" signs, which were accompanied by a
fall in interest rates on treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
A report published by the Lebanese Bankers' Association
Thursday also indicated improving economic conditions with a
sharp rise in construction activity and new business start-ups.
</P>
<P>
Banking performance also registered a slight improvement in
total lending in Lebanese pound, which increased by 1.3 percent
in the public sector and 1.55 percent in the private sector, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign currencies lending, however, dropped by 1.33
percent, suggesting lower interest rates were having a positive
impact on dollarization.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that exports of manufactured products
recorded a 19 percent drop between January and February, while
imports of machinery and equipment fell by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Volume of shares on the Beirut Stock Exchange rose by 36
percent in February, amounting to 1.8 million shares traded,
with total value of 22.3 million dollars compared to 16.4
million dollars in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
