<HEADLINE> Largest Inkslab Made in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 25 (Xinhua) -- An inkslab weighing 1.2 tons, the
largest one in the country, was finished recently in east China's
Fujian province.
</P>
<P>
The giant ink container, measuring two meters long and 1.26
meters in width, has 100 flying dragons and eight horses carved on
its body.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhengen, a skillful mason, found the huge stone in North
China's Hebei province, and spent more than one year making the
giant inkslab with many traditional carving methods.
</P>
<P>
Qi Gong, the country's best-known calligrapher wrote
inscriptions for the inkstone. The massive ink holder is to be
auctioned in Xiamen when Hong Kong returns to the motherland.
</P>
</TEXT>
