<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Scientists Discover Genes Enabling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Israeli scientists have
discovered a group of genes that make tomatoes resistant to wilt
disease, according to a report by the latest issue of the Plant
Cell.
</P>
<P>
The findings by scientists at the Weizmann Institute of Science
is expected to speed up the breeding of new disease-resistant
varieties and reduce the need for chemical spraying.
</P>
<P>
Wild tomatoes are naturally resistant to wilt disease spread
by the soil-borne Fusarium oxysporum fungus (Lycopersici
strain). Once a widespread blight plaguing tomato crops, Fusarium
wilt disease is largely brought under control through classical
breeding techniques.
</P>
<P>
However, breeding new varieties through this method is a
laborious process that can take years because it entails
producing many successive generations of hybrid plants in which
the undesirable traits have been eliminated but the beneficial
ones retained.
</P>
<P>
The new study facilitates this process by providing molecular
markers allowing breeders to simply trace the genetic makeup of
new hybrids rather than test for it at each stage. The findings
also pave the way for genetically engineered new varieties with
an optimal mixture of desired properties.
</P>
<P>
"In the absence of genes that endow plants with natural
resistance to disorders such as wilt disease, farmers must rely
on extensive chemical spraying and soil treatment," says
Prof. Fluhr, a member of the Weizmann Institute's Plant Genetics
Department.
</P>
<P>
"By imparting natural self-defense capabilities to plants, we
reduce the amount of dangerous chemicals entering the
environment", the professor added.
</P>
<P>
The newly identified genes are also of primary importance
because they form the plant's first line of defense against
Fusarium attack. Acting as regulatory switches, they induce the
release of various defensive agents such as destructive oxygen
molecules that bombard the disease-causing organism, or enzymes
that chew away at it.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover," Fluhr says, "the methodology we have helped for
isolating resistance genes should make it possible to design new
resistance genes and transfer them to various crops where they
are lacking."
</P>
<P>
The Weizmann Institute of Science is a major center of
scientific research and graduate study located in Rehovot in
central Israel. Its 2,400 scientists, students and support staff
are engaged in more than 850 research projects across the
spectrum of contemporary science. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Hopes for Cooperation with Norway in Shipbuilding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier Zou Jiahua
said here today that China is ready to cooperate with Norway in
shipbuilding industry, transferring the latter's hi-tech and
training shipbuilding personnel for China.
</P>
<P>
Zou expressed the wish at a meeting with Erik Tonseth,
president and chief executive officer of the Norwegian Kvaerner
Group, which specializes in manufacturing hydraulic generating
sets and shipbuilding.
</P>
<P>
After briefing the Norwegian visitors on China's principles in
conducting international cooperation, namely "equality and mutual
benefit, long-term cooperation and common development," Zou said
he hopes that Kvaerner Group will cooperate with Chinese firms to
transfer its hi-tech, help train Chinese personnel in
shipbuilding, and conduct joint research and development,
designing, and manufacturing in the industry.
</P>
<P>
China has witnessed great progress in shipbuilding over the
past dozens of years, Zou said, adding that he welcomes Kvaerner
to participate in bidding some contracted projects in the
Three-Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
Tonseth said Kvaerner wishes to share its hi-tech with China
and all other countries in the world and his Group is ready to
cooperate with China in shipbuilding, hydraulic generation, and
other industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian visitors are here as guests of the China State
Shipbuilding Corporation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
