<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Hosts Sino-Foreign Discussion on Air Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Over 120 experts from 13
countries and regions attended an international conference on air
cargo in Beijing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was sponsored by the US's McDonnell Douglas Corp. to discuss
China's air cargo market, developing and operating an air cargo
transport service, and global maintenance and support.
</P>
<P>
Shen Yuankang, deputy director of the Civil Aviation
Administration of China (CAAC), told the conference that in 1996,
Chinese airlines had 8.06 billion ton/kms, 55.55 million
passengers, and 1.15 million tons of cargoes.
</P>
<P>
Air freight will grow at a faster rate than passenger traffic
in China for a long time to come and steps are being taken to meet
the growing demand. These include market research on cargo flow,
opening air freight routes, building freight bases, using more
agents for faster service, air-land and sea-air transportation,
and a computerized network to improve sales, movement, and
storage, Shen told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
John L. Fugh, the president of McDonnell Douglas-China, said
that he was glad that such an important conference could be held
in Beijing. "With the rapid economic growth in China and in other
Asian countries, the demand for air freight will become even
huger. We hope the conference can help air companies and related
departments to have a better knowledge of the market demand so as
to seize the chances."
</P>
<P>
Ed Bavaria, deputy president of Douglas Aircraft Co., said at
the conference that the rapid economic development in China has
accelerated the growth of air transportation, and the air
transportation market shows great potential. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
