<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Chinese Province Increasing Trade with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The capital of northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province is trying to improve the stagnant conditions
in trade and economic cooperation with Far East and Siberia in
Russian.
</P>
<P>
Harbin is the closest city to Russia and has worked out a plan
to promote trade and economic cooperation with Siberia and
Russia's far east. The plan lists the Russian cities of
Yekaterinburg, Khabarovsk, Vladivostok, and Nakhodka as major
trading partners.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for trade volume to increase to two billion US
dollars worth annually by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Industry insiders say that the city's measures dovetail with
Russia's strategy to develop its eastern areas and advance
economic relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Russian trade saw a decline in 1994 because of trade
policy adjustments, market changes, and the poor quality of some
Chinese goods, said Zeng Xianfu, deputy director of the Harbin
City Bureau of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Wang Guangtao, Harbin's mayor, paid an official visit last year
to Russia and worked with local governments to set up a
Sino-Russian Economic Coordinating Committee to remove obstacles
to further trade.
</P>
<P>
There are good prospects for increasing industrial and
agricultural cooperation in the far east area and northeast
China. The Russians say they hope China will join in the effort to
open up the resource-rich area, which could boost regional
economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Harbin plans to have regular displays of quality and name-brand
goods in the Far East and in Siberia to re-gain the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
