<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Probe Foreign Exchange Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government said on
Thursday it might be forced to introduce appropriate measures to
curtail persistent increase in foreign exchange demand and ensure
that all disbursements are properly accounted for.
</P>
<P>
It is observed this reflects the government's concern over the
excessive demand for foreign exchange which overshot projection
for the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Industry Minister Lt.-Gen. Mohammed Haladu who gave the
warning said that the phenomenal increase in foreign exchange
demand was "unacceptable" especially against the background that
no cogent reasons were given by banks and end users to justify
the trend.
</P>
<P>
"In other words, the impact of that demand has not been
positively felt in the productive sectors of the economy, but
limited to demands for basic travel allowance which in most cases
are counter productive," the minister said, quoted by press
reports today.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian banks and end users get foreign exchange mainly
through the autonomous foreign exchange market (AFEM). They bid
for foreign exchange they require at the weekly session of the
AFEM in accordance with the exchange rate set by the Central Bank
of Nigeria, which intervenes the weekly session with an aim of
stabilizing the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has in fact adopted some measures to curtail
excessive demand for foreign exchange this year. Among the
measures are the directive to banks to submit document to back up
their request for foreign exchange in the first 13 sessions of
the AFEM and the devaluation of the naira from 80 to 85 to one
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Despite the measures, the demand has consistently been on the
high side, prompting the central bank to swoop on some banks last
week to check their books.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, demand for foreign exchange rose from
76,234 dollars in the first AFEM session in January to 71.164
million dollars last week, when aggregate demand came to 922
million.
</P>
<P>
Total projected outlay for the funding of AFEM is 2.7 billion
dollars for the whole of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
