<HEADLINE> World Bank Aids Chengdu to Fight Chronic Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Chengdu, the capital city of
southwest China's Sichuan Province, has received 1.16 million US
dollars loaned by the World Bank to improve the health of its
residents.
</P>
<P>
The loan, along with more than 10 million yuan (about 1.2
million US dollars) from the city government will be used mainly
for projects to prevent and treat chronic diseases.
</P>
<P>
Chengdu is one of the earliest Chinese cities that implemented
the prevention and treatment of chronic diseases, and is China's
largest monitoring station for the causes of death.
</P>
<P>
The chronic diseases and death causes of the city's four
million residents have been reported from seven districts and two
counties since the monitoring work began 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The city joined the World Bank's health-improving project as a
representative of middle-sized cities in southwest and northwest
parts of China. It will build a unified network for health
improvement under the five-year project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
