<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers in Mao's Hometown See Great Changes in Their Lives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- When Mao Qiman and Xie Yingming
wed in 1977 in Shaoshan Village, the home of late Chairman Mao
Zedong in central China's Hunan Province, they only had a one-room
house to live in.
</P>
<P>
Now however, Mao Qiman, a former farmer who is now a
contractor, owns a two-storey building valued at more than 100,000
yuan (12,000 US dollars). His family has a color TV, refrigerator,
and washing machine that Chinese urbanites have, but also a car
and a mobile telephone that only richer folk have.
</P>
<P>
Mao Shiyu, the party secretary of 450-family village, says that
over 30 percent of its households are as rich as Mao Qiman, thanks
to the reform and opening-up policy of the late '70s, as well as
the fame of the late great leader.
</P>
<P>
Mao Shiyu says that farmers in his village become wealthier by
using its status as a state-level tourism spot, by selling tourist
goods, and opening restaurants and hotels, to augment their
farming.
</P>
<P>
The village has 130 small hotels and restaurants and more than
300 booths selling tourist goods. Some farmers also work for a
building company or run a transportation business.
</P>
<P>
Per capita net income of Shaoshan villagers got up to 5,200
yuan (650 dollars), 2.7 percent higher than the country's average
in rural areas in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Seventy years ago, Hunanese farmers started a movement and
demanded that their basic food and clothing needs be met. Mao
Zedong, who toured mountainous Hunan at that time to study the
situation, described to local people an imaginary future for their
homeland, saying there would be highways built chessboard style,
with every village being served by the spiderweb-like traffic and
power grid.
</P>
<P>
In visiting Shaoshan now, one can see that the imagination made
by Mao 70 years ago was not fertile enough to include all the
changes that have taken place by now.
</P>
<P>
According to Peng Chuqiao, mayor of Shaoshan City, nearly 90
percent of the farmers in his city have moved into several-story
buildings. The old farm houses of the past are seldom seen.
</P>
<P>
In the city, every village has paved roads, 99.8 percent of the
rural households have electricity, 80 percent of the villages have
program-controlled telephone service, 94 percent of the rural
households have color TV sets, and each village has a reading
room. The whole Shaoshan City, including the Shaoshan Village, is
leading a happy life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Forecast Moderately Fast Growth in China in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China's national economy is
expected to maintain the trend of moderately rapid growth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This year, inflation will be brought under effective control,
the income and spending of residents will continue to increase
steadily, the state revenues will rise, and the foreign trade
sector will accelerate.
</P>
<P>
These predictions were delivered here today in a report by a
group of economists from the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences
and the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In the report, entitled "Analysis and Forecasts of China's
Economic Situation (Spring of 1997 Report)," the economists show
their cautious optimism about the country's economic situation in
1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the growth of China's gross domestic
product may reach 10 percent, a bit higher over the figure of 9.7
percent in the previous year, while investment in fixed assets is
expected to match the previous year's level of 12.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The economists predict a five percent inflation rate of retail
prices and a seven percent rise in the prices of consumer goods
and services, while the per-capita incomes of urban and rural
residents are projected to increase by 4.9 percent and 5.3
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The state exchequer is expected to receive 869 billion yuan and
to spend 912 billion in 1997, up 16.6 percent and 15.2 percent
respectively, resulting in a deficit of 53 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the savings of individuals are projected to increase
by 29 percent to reach 4,971 billion yuan, while the
newly-extended bank loans and newly-issued currency are expected
to top 1,113 billion yuan and 125 billion yuan respectively.
</P>
<P>
The year's imports and exports are predicted to be 153 billion
US dollars and 165 billion US dollars, increasing by 9.9 percent
and 9.0 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
While analyzing the country's economic situation, the report
describes the current macro-economic control as the most favorable of
the 90s and it says that the situation is the direct result of the
successful "soft-landing" of the Chinese economy last year.
</P>
<P>
The report says that there are still many problems and
contradictions in the economy.
</P>
<P>
It adds that the government should adhere to the principle of
"advancing while maintaining stability, invigorating the economy
while exercising relatively tight control" in 1997, so as to create
better conditions for the economic growth during the Ninth
Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) period and beyond. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
