<HEADLINE> Nepali Group Demands Scrapping of Rhino Gift Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A local environmental group
here has demanded the government to immediately scrap a plan to
give two rhinos to Britain as a gift, a press release said today.
</P>
<P>
The Nepal Forum of Environmental Journalists (NFEJ) said in its
press release that it is not right to send rhinos, an endangered
species in Nepal, abroad when the country lacks a clear and
transparent policy on wildlife conservation.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government pledged two years ago to dispatch two
female unicorn rhinos to the London Zoo of Britain as gifts for
the purpose of scientific research.
</P>
<P>
According to the NFEJ, final preparations for trapping two
rhinos in the Chitwan National Wildlife Park in West Nepal have
been completed.
</P>
<P>
An NFEJ delegation with Environment Minister Vidya Bhandari
Thursday demanding an immediate halt to the preparations under way
for sending the rhinos to Britain, it said.
</P>
<P>
The NFEJ is expected to submit a written appeal today to Prime
Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand and concerned ministers for
aborting the rhino gift plan until the government formulates a
transparent policy regarding such cases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
