<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Power Sector Requires Huge Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- With the demand for power
increasing by the day, India's power sector requires huge
investment, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
It has been estimated that the capacity addition required for
the next 10 years would be 111,500 megawatts (mw), of which 44,000
mw is estimated during 1996-2001 and an additional 67,500 mw
during 2001-2006.
</P>
<P>
The total investment required for building the required
infrastructure for power would be about 6,244 billion rupees
(175.88 billion U.S. dollars) at fixed prices, of which 2,464
billion rupees (69.4 billion dollars) would be required between
1996 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
Keeping in view the enormous size of the financial resources
required and the inability of the government to fund the same
through budgetary allocations, the Indian Electricity Act (1910)
and the Electricity (Supply) Act (1948) were amended to bring
about new legal, administrative and financial environment for
private enterprise in the power sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
