<HEADLINE> Russian Firms Cheated of Big Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Six Russian companies involved in
a joint venture in Thailand have accused their local partner of
cheating them of 980,000 U.S. dollars, a local newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The Russian firms under the Krasnoyarsk Group, recently decided
to take the matter to the press after their complaints were
ignored by local law enforcement authorities, the Bangkok Post
said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian firms signed an agreement to set up a joint venture
named Thaisib International in May 1992 with its local partner the
Almaz Group to build a factory to manufacture garments for export
to Russia, Europe, the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Russians alleged that they put 980,000 dollars in two
installments into the venture to purchase land for the factory and
the rest to be used as equity.
</P>
<P>
However, they said that in 1994, they found that the joint
venture located in Bangkok was not operational any more and it was
registered with a capital of only 2 million baht (80,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Their local partner told them that a factory was being built in
Samutprakan Province, yet the Russians said they found no land had
been purchased for the factory and their attempts to seek
clarification ran into a brick wall.
</P>
<P>
The Russian firms last May took the matter to the Economic
Crime Investigation Division of the Thai Police Department, which
has so far failed to take any action against their local partner,
the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
