<HEADLINE> 9.1-Percent Industrial Growth Recorded in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- India has recorded a
9.1-percent overall industrial growth rate in the first eight
months of the 1996-97 fiscal year, responding favorably to the
policy changes, reforms and incentives offered by the government.
</P>
<P>
The industrial growth, which was 0.6 percent in 1991-92, rose
to 11.7 percent during 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
The figures were contained in the Annual Handbook of Statistics
1996, released by the Confederation of Indian Industry (CII) here
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The industrial growth was led by the capital goods sector,
which recorded a growth of 23.8 percent during 1994-95, indicating
a change from earlier years when growth used to be led by the
consumer durables sector.
</P>
<P>
The growth also became broad-based and spread to all sectors,
said the statistics handbook.
</P>
<P>
According to the CII release, the small-scale sector
contributed nearly 35 percent of the total industrial output apart
from being a major player in export and employment.
</P>
<P>
The release said the country's exports in 1995-96 amounted to
31,797 million U.S. dollars, registering an increased of 20.8
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
