<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fosters More Minority Nationality Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China has given great attention to
training and selecting officials of ethnic groups and so far has
formed a 2.48-million-strong troop of national minority officials.
</P>
<P>
Early in 1947, China founded its first autonomous region in
northern China's Inner Mongolia and later spread its practice of
regional autonomy of minority nationalities in its other parts.
</P>
<P>
The fostering and selecting of ethic groups' officials is one
of the major parts of the regional autonomy policy.
</P>
<P>
Guan Xiumei, 33, deputy director of a Hohhot woolen mill, was
an ordinary worker of ethic Manchu group 16 years ago. Hohhot was
the regional capital of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region. She
was promoted to a factory cadre after being a spinner for eight
years.
</P>
<P>
She was selected as a national model worker when she was a
spinner and showed talent in work arrangement.
</P>
<P>
After her promotion, the high school graduate completed a
three-year study of courses arranged by a correspondence
university during her spare time.
</P>
<P>
Guan Xiumei told Xinhua that "I was too shy to meet with
reporters when I just became a cadre of my factory. And I would
blush when talking with strangers. Now I would like to answer any
of your questions confidently."
</P>
<P>
Most of workers and factory cadres expressed satisfaction with
Guan's performance.
</P>
<P>
Guan is only one example of millions of China's minority
nationality officials. China has 55 minority nationalities and
Manchu nationality is of them.
</P>
<P>
In early 1950s, the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region had only
registered less than 300 national minority officials. The number
has reached 163,000, or 23.3 percent of the region's total, which
exceeds the ratio between the minority population and Han people
in the region.
</P>
<P>
So far, China has set up five autonomous region, 30 autonomous
prefectures, and 121 autonomous counties or banners, with a
minority population of 103 million.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous regions include Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region,
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, Tibet Autonomous Region, and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
The leading government officials of the autonomous areas are
all ethnic minorities. In Tibet, the number of Tibetan officials and
officials of other ethnic groups accounts for 70 percent of the
region's total. In the Korean Autonomous Prefecture of Yanbian in
northeast China, the Korean population accounts for 39.9 percent
of the prefecture's total while the number of Korean officials
accounts for 45.9. The number of Korean officials at prefecture
level accounts for 53.9 of the total.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of China and the government at various
levels have been treating the promotion of minority officials as a
strategic task. They send national minority officials to cadre
schools, secondary schools, or universities for systematic
trainings and send some of them to study abroad or make overseas
investigation tours.
</P>
<P>
So far, 66.2 percent of the minority officials have specialized
technical skills and many of them are professors, researchers,
senior technicians, physicians-in-charge, or experts in various
fields.
</P>
<P>
Among hundreds of academicians of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, China's top natural sciences research institution, 11
are of Mongolian, Manchu, Hui, or other ethnic groups.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Ratifies Chemical Weapons Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Following a two-day heated
debate, the United States Senate today ratified the Chemical
Weapons Convention enabling it to participate in the treaty when
it takes effect on April 29.
</P>
<P>
The approval is a big foreign policy victory for President Bill
Clinton, who has pushed hard for the ratification of the treaty by
launching a high-profile lobbying campaign.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, which has been signed by 164 countries and ratified
by 74, was approved in the Senate by a vote of 74 against 26. It
was more than the necessary two-thirds majority for treaty
approval.
</P>
<P>
All Democrats voted for the treaty while Republican were
divided.
</P>
<P>
The treaty bans the use, development, production, stockpiling
and transfer of chemical weapons and requires the destruction of
existing stockpiles in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the vote, the administration allies succeeded in
eliminating a killer amendment proposed by the opponents of the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
The senate voted 71-29 to reject the amendment that would bar
the U.S. ratification until Iran, Iraq and Syria had accepted the
pact.
</P>
<P>
The ratification of the treaty came after Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, one of the leading critics, reversed his
position and turned to support the treaty.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the U.S. is marginally better off with it (the
treaty) than without it," said Lott in a Senate speech.
</P>
<P>
The ratification also benefited from a letter of Clinton to
Lott earlier today.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Clinton promised the Senate that he would
withdraw from the Chemical Weapons Convention if the pact
inadvertently resulted in the spread of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Lott and Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, had been major opponents to the convention, which will
come into being on April 29 with or without U.S. participation.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Clinton said he was "prepared to withdraw from
the treaty" if other countries used its provisions to proliferate
chemical weapons technology and endanger U.S. security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Fast Thai Economic Recovery Not in Sight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Continued fall by the private
investment index has indicated that Thailand's economy might not
stage a rebound in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The index dropped to 94.8 points in February, its lowest level
since 1992, compared to a peak of 125 points in mid-1995 when the
economy was buoyant.
</P>
<P>
Economic statistics for January and February announced by the
central bank Thursday showed that the country's economy is still
slow in turning around.
</P>
<P>
Exports, one of the main hopeful sectors for the country to
boost its economic growth, declined 0.3 percent year-on-year for
the first two months of this year, due mainly to agricultural
exports, which declined 17.6 percent and fishery exports dropped
6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing sector exports increased a mere 2.2 percent, and
high-technology goods increased only 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, labor-intensive goods decreased 9.9 percent and raw
material goods decreased 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The private investment index which declined to a low activity
level, brought about reduced imports of capital goods in February
by 8 percent, the third straight month of decline.
</P>
<P>
The poor economic performance for the first two months of this
year indicates that first quarter economic figures are likely to
remain as sluggish as the first two months.
</P>
<P>
Some economists say that the sluggishness could prompt the
central bank to revise downward its projected 6.9 percent economic
growth rate for the year.
</P>
<P>
To spur investment, an interest rate cut is necessary and
long-term interest rates may be allowed to fall in the second
quarter if they have no negative effect on the country's economic
stability.
</P>
<P>
However, bankers say even though the average interbank rate in
February was down to 8.34 percent from 14.94 percent in January,
it was too early to say that interest rates would decline.
</P>
<P>
Positive sides were that current account deficit in February
was the lowest in several months, at 14.7 billion baht (588
million U.S. dollars), down from 22.5 billion baht (900 million
dollars) in January, and inflation was 4.3 percent, lower than
earlier estimates for the entire year of 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although inflation seems to be improving at present, a rise in
civil servant salaries, likely to be 5 percent and to be
introduced in October, will bring about higher prices.
</P>
<P>
To stimulate the country's economic growth, improved confidence
in the country's economy was required, said Kleothong Hetrakul,
director of the Economic Research Department of the Bank of
Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
