<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five-Nation Accord Significant, Says Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The agreement on mutual
reduction of military forces in border areas between China and
four countries - Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan -
is of great significance for Central Asian nations, a Kyrgyz
newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The accord, signed in Moscow earlier today by presidents of the
five countries, consolidates regional security and constitutes
another step toward multinational cooperation, said the
capital-based Bishkek evening newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony and the subsequent press conference lasted
only a few hours, but heads of state of the five countries had
prepared for the day for a long time, it said.
</P>
<P>
The document, the first agreement of its kind in the
Asia-Pacific region, was a result of more than seven years of
negotiations between China and the four countries.
</P>
<P>
It followed an agreement on confidence-building in the military
field in border areas, signed by the five presidents in China's
largest city, Shanghai, in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Statesmen and diplomats said the Shanghai document was a unique
accord which guaranteed peace and stability in Central Asia, said
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
China and Russia, which initialled the two agreements, had
contributed enormously to solving the border problems, the
newspaper said, adding that the other three nations had also
participated actively.
</P>
<P>
Under the Moscow agreement, valid until the end of the year
2020, all parties will reduce military forces in border areas to
the minimum level suiting only defensive needs, and in accord with
their good-neighborly and friendly ties.
</P>
<P>
China shares with the other four countries more than 7,000
kilometers of border lines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
