<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Set to Solve Unemployment Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government is
planning to establish an islandwide network of industrial estates
to solve her unemployment problem, according to Ministry of
Industrial Development sources today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that a program is underway to provide 60,000
jobs under the first stage and 100,000 jobs under the second stage
of 10 industrial estates which have already been launched.
</P>
<P>
under this program a further 23 sites have been identified
following feasibility studies and environmental tests.
Entrepreneurs were keen to set up ventures at these sites.
</P>
<P>
The sources noted, "Basically there is a growing demand to
develop industrial sites which would help generate employment at
the provincial level."
</P>
<P>
A garment industrial estate at Karadeniya in the south was
opened recently. It would immediately provide jobs to 250 persons
and another 750 persons during its second stage.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government has adopted various measures to solve
its unemployment problem in the past few years. However, there are
still over one million unemployed in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Foreign Trade Deficit Keeps Increasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The foreign trade deficit of the
Czech Republic in the first quarter of this year stood at 40.2
billion Koruny (1.4 billion U.S. dollars), up 47.8 percent over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of this year, exports amounted to 148
billion Koruny (5.1 billion dollars) while imports exceeded 188
billion Koruny (6.5 billion dollars) as shown by the latest figures
provided by the National Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Less competitive products, fewer demands from its main West
trading partners and unchecked imports by some domestic units all
contribute to the huge trade deficit in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The 161 billion Koruny (5.6 billion dollars) deficit in 1996,
accounting for 8.5 percent of the gross domestic product, goes
beyond the generally-regarded security line.
</P>
<P>
Experts expect the foreign trade deficit this year to break
through the 200 billion Koruny (6.9 billion dollars) mark.
</P>
<P>
The Czech government has worked out a set of measures to
encourage exports and restrict imports.
</P>
<P>
These measures include the setting up of a system under which
importers are required to deposit 20 percent of the total imports
in cash to the designated banks as guarantees. No interest will
be paid on the deposits. The system came into force on April 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Imports Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Despite the Colombian
government's import control measures, the country's imports in the
first quarter of this year grew 5.5 percent over the same period
last year, to 5.213 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But import taxes, part of the government's economic emergency
measures to curb spending, had resulted in a moderate March import
bill of 1.668 billion dollars, 5.8 percent down from a year
before, the Colombian Foreign Trade Institute said.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the major exporter to Colombia in the
quarter, providing a third of the country's imports.
</P>
