<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Nuclear Power Stations Rise to 443 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The number of nuclear power
stations in the world has risen to 443 at present, the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) said today.
</P>
<P>
Their overall generated energy now accounts for 17 percent of
the world total of 2.3 million megawatts hour, figures indicate.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, five new nuclear power stations were put into
operation, and another one is to be added this year.
</P>
<P>
At present, 14 countries are building 36 nuclear power
stations, IAEA says.
</P>
<P>
In Lithuania, nuclear power generates 83.4 percent of its total
electric energy, followed by France with 77.4 percent, Belgium
57.2 percent and Sweden 52.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The United States has 110 nuclear power stations, France 57 and
Japan 53, IAEA statistics show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Company Uncovers Spanish Galleon Treasures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A United States company has
retrieved treasures worth two million U.S. dollars from a Spanish
galleon which sank in the sea off Ecuador during Spain's colonial
rule in South America.
</P>
<P>
German Moro, the president of the South American Discoveries
Company, said today that more than 5,000 silver coins, ingots,
plates, candelabra and other objects of the same metal have been
salvaged since March 18.
</P>
<P>
Some belongings of passengers or crew had also been recovered,
including a gold coin, gold rings and silver combs and buckles.
</P>
<P>
Other discoveries included a large quantity of cannon balls,
nails, musket bullets, and ceramic shards.
</P>
<P>
Moro said the treasure the galleon was carrying could have been
worth about 2.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The salvage task will last at least three months more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
