<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Sack Impotent Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
will soon sack a number of senior officials who have failed to
implement his Anti-Corruption Program.
</P>
<P>
Vasily Durdinets, chairman of the Coordination Committee
against Corruption and Organized Crime, said Kuchma had strongly
criticized leaders of some ministries and bodies for their
inability to implement the Anti-corruption Program.
</P>
<P>
He named the ministries of transport, economy, and coal
industry, and the Donetsk and Lugansk Oblasts (administrative
regions).
</P>
<P>
Durdinets, also a deputy prime minister, added that Kuchma made
the criticisms at a meeting of the Coordination Committee today,
which was also attended by Director of the National Security
Bureau Vladimir Radchenko and Interior Minister Yuri Kravchenko.
</P>
<P>
Misuse of governemnt funds in the Donetsk Oblast and the
Lugansk Oblast cropped up two weeks after Kuchma instituted the
Anti-Corruption Program, which aims to investigate all government
officials by October 1, and fire those who are found to be related
to graft or criminal groups.
</P>
<P>
Durdinets proposed to Kuchma at the meeting of Coordination
Committee that Minister of Transport, Alexandr Zolotoverkh, and
Deputy Economic Minister Vladimir Naumenko should be dismissed due
to their failure to tackle graft in their ministries.
</P>
<P>
Durdinets said that since the Anti-Corruption Program came into
effect, criminal activities had shown a downward tendency and the
detection rate had increased.
</P>
<P>
However, Durdinets stressed that the overall situation in the
country was not reason for optimism, especially in places like
Kiev, Crimea and Odessa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
