<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- An agreement on mutual reduction of military forces in
border areas between China and four countries, Russia, Kazakhstan,
Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, was signed in Moscow yesterday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first agreement of its kind signed in the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
-- Presidents of the five nations hailed the agreement as "an
unprecedented achievement." In separate speeches delivered after
the signing of the accord in the Kremlin, the presidents
unanimously extolled the document as of historic significance to
security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng met yesterday with former Canadian Prime
Minister Martin Brian Mulroney, former US Secretary of State
George Shultz, and other international dignitaries from North
America, Western Europe, and the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
These dignitaries were here in China to attend the second
session of the China International Trust and Investment
Corp. (CITIC) International Advisory Council, which was held in
Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua News Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin and his Tajik counterpart Emomali
Rakhmonov hailed Thursday the five-nation agreement on military
reduction in border areas as a document of "historical
significance."
</P>
<P>
Making the comment when meeting with Rakhmonov, Jiang said that
yesterday marks an important date in the growth of relations
between China and neighboring Tajikistan, Russia, Kazakhstan and
Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
-- The Xinhua Bookstore Chain should be built into a first-rate
national book distribution system to help improve the quality of
the Chinese nation and promote socialist ethical and cultural
progress, Premier Li Peng said yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The premier made the call when meeting with representatives
from the bookstore's national chain at its 60th anniversary
celebration.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China yesterday expressed strong displeasure over a meeting
between US President Clinton and the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
Clinton joined a meeting between Vice-President Al Gore and the
Dalai Lama on Wednesday at the White House in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told the Dalai Lama that he would urge China to open
direct dialogue with him.
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng yesterday reaffirmed China's wish to enhance
technological co-operation and exchanges in various forms with
Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in a written congratulatory message to the
Asia-Europe Expert Meeting on Technological Co-operation, which
opened yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
-- The Ministry of Labor has urged implementation of the State
Council's decree for a five-say national work week by May 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Under the government decree, which was issued two years ago,
employees in government offices, institutions and enterprises are
guaranteed a two-day weekend beginning May 1, 1995. They are also
entitled to an annual paid vacation.  
