<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Car Maker Performs Well in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Italian auto group Fiat earned
2.37 trillion lire (1.39 billion U.S. dollars) in net profit last
year, up 9.4 percent from 1995, the company said today.
</P>
<P>
The Turin-based group, Italy's largest private industrial
giant, said its turnover rose by 4 percent in 1996 to 78 trillion
lire (45.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Despite the company's recent involvement into a corruption
scandal and its chairman Cesare Romiti's 18-month jail sentence
earlier this month, the board meeting today predicted equally good
results for this year.
</P>
<P>
It reported that turnover was up 4.4 percent to 20.8 trillion
lire (12.2 billion dollars) in the first quarter of this year. Car
sales rose by 25 percent in March and are expected to stay at the
same level in April.
</P>
<P>
"The group has reached its new objectives in spite of an
economic context which is difficult throughout the world," said
Cesare Romiti, the most prominent business figure convicted since
the government started an anti-corruption campaign in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Romiti, along with a former finance director of Fiat, was
sentenced on April 9 on charges of falsifying accounts of more
than 30 billion lire (17.6 million dollars) since the 1980s to
make payments to political parties and top Fiat managers abroad.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the Rome state prosecutor's office is asking the
two top executives to stand another trial for allegedly paying 300
billion lire (175.9 million dollars) bribes to political parties
between 1983 and 1992 to ensure construction contracts.
</P>
<P>
The company said it will pay the same dividends for 1996 as the
previous year, 100 lire dividends per ordinary share and 130 lire
per savings share. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
