<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Budget Size to Be 10 Percent Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's national budget for
the next fiscal year 1997-98 is likely to be announced with 10
percent increase in total volume and around 5.3 percent deficit of
the gross domestic product, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the first budget document which has been completed
by the budget wing, more than 560 billion rupees (about 14 billion
U.S. dollars) has been based on overall 10 percent increase on the
overall savings, informed sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
During the current year, domestic savings well surpassed the
target by scoring an additional 10 percent on what was fixed.
</P>
<P>
As a paradigm shift, the government has decided to manage
supply side of the capital flow rather than curtailing expenditure
and narrowing down budget deficit, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Based on this understanding, the basic document has been
prepared by suggesting curtailment in the civil non-development
expenditures, proportional increase in the development expenditure
to carry on an ambitious development policy, and meeting the
deficit through short-term bank and private borrowings, they said.
</P>
<P>
A 5.2 percent gap between sources and expenditures, which is
about 30 billion rupees (about 750 million U.S. dollars) would be
filled through bank and other private borrowings, they said. In
this connection, a dialogue is already underway with the Citybank
and private sources based in the Gulf and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Once again this year debt serving would consume the biggest
chunk of total resources amounting to 38 percent of the budget,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
To curtail the current running expenditure, the government has
planned to downsize its overall strength by more than 50 percent
and several ministries have also been planned to be merged, they
said. These measures would be announced in the first week of May.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Accused of Using Double Medical Standards in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Thai Red Cross officials recently
pointed out that the U.S.-funded researchers are practicing double
standards in their medical experiments in Thailand, a local
newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The researchers, who conducted anti-AIDS treatment tests on
pregnant women in Thailand, gave some mothers a placebo, which is
unacceptable by some U.S. patient advocacy groups as it might
result in unnecessary death of infants, according to the Bangkok
Post.
</P>
<P>
Prapan Phanuphak, director of the Thai Red Cross Society's
program on AIDS, noted that the U.S. was displaying double
standards when they funded researches to find cheaper alternative
to expensive treatments with AZT, a drug which helps prevent the
spread of AIDS from mother to baby.
</P>
<P>
Some AIDS experts in Thailand said that Thailand should adopt
research standards to prevent unethical medical experiments from
being conducted on Thais.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Ethical Committee recently approved a proposal by
the communicable diseases control U.S.-Thai collaboration center
to carry out a study to minimize the impact of AZT on mothers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Implement New Tax Despite Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 25 (Xinhua) --The Nepali government is
determined to implement the new Value Added Tax (VAT) later this
year despite strong opposition from business circles, Finance
Minister Rabindra Nath Sharma said.
</P>
<P>
The government will not yield to any kind of protest against
the new tax regime which is to be imposed from November, the
minister said at a round-table discussion meeting on VAT held here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nepali businessmen have been staging protests in different
parts of the country against the VAT tax, which the government
expects to increase national revenue and prevent tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
They said Nepal's tax authorities and business community lack
adequate preparations for the new tax regime and the VAT would
adversely affect the overall economic development in the country.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen were still misguided by the perception that they
can press the government to scrap VAT by staging protest programs,
the finance minister said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the government will ensure businessmen's
competitive capacities under the VAT by widening the tax coverage
rather than increasing the average tax rate.
</P>
<P>
He accused some businessmen of spreading rumors of price hikes
after the VAT implementation among the general public.
</P>
<P>
Such rumors were baseless, the minister said, explaining that
the new VAT system will replace the existing hotel tax,
entertainment tax, sales tax and excise.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the government would double its tax revenue
to nearly 2 million U.S. dollars a year through implementing the
VAT regime.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Naval Chief Asked to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif has asked Naval Chief Admiral Mansurul Haq to resign in the
wake of widespread allegations of irregularities leveled against
him, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Sharif ordered Admiral Mansurul Haq, who called on the prime
minister Thursday, to resign immediately since he is facing
accusations of alleged corruption, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The naval chief has tendered his resignation to President
Farooq Leghari according to the reports.  
