<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit with Thailand Declines in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The United States saw a deficit
of 4.1 billion U.S. dollars in its trade with Thailand last year,
a decrease of 824 million dollars or 16.3 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
The decrease was mainly attributed to the increased U.S.
exports to Thailand, according to a report from the U.S. Embassy
in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. merchandise exports to Thailand posted 7.2 billion
dollars in value last year, an increase of 809 million dollars or
12.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
While the U.S. imports from Thailand recorded 11.3 billion
dollars, a decline of 15 million dollars or 0.1 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the stock of U.S. foreign direct
investment (FDI) in Thailand rose 22.9 percent to 4.6 billion
dollars in 1995 compared with 1994.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the U.S. FDI in Thailand is concentrated largely on
the manufacturing and petroleum sectors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
