<HEADLINE> Andean Community Study Peru's Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Four member countries of the
Andean Community trade bloc, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, and
Venezuela, will create a commission to study the consequences of
Peru's withdrawal from the bloc.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Frenddy Rojas Parra, Venezuelan
development minister, who attended the recently concluded Andean
summit in Sucre, Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
The Andean Community member nations all considered Peru's
participation important for the bloc, Rojas Parra said.
</P>
<P>
Peru announced on April 11 its decision to leave the group,
which was founded in 1969.
</P>
<P>
Peru claimed the group was not living up to its mission of
creating freer trade in the region. But the move came after other
members rejected its proposals for entering the group's common
external tariff.
</P>
<P>
During the recent summit, the Andean Community group pledged to
begin talks with Panama on an agreement incorporating Pananma in
the bloc in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The summit also confirmed the bloc's commitment to concluding
negotiations for a free trade agreement with South America's
biggest trade bloc, Mercosur, and joining negotiations for a Free
Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA). 
</P>
</TEXT>
