<HEADLINE> Myanmar Leader Calls for Boosting Paddy Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Senior-General Than
Shwe has called for boosting paddy production in the country in
the 1997-98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting on boosting paddy production here
Thursday, Than Shwe, who is chairman of the Myanmar State Law and
Order Restoration Council, stressed that the nation must be built
on the agriculture sector, official paper The New Light of Myanmar
reported today.
</P>
<P>
He said paddy, the major crop of the nation, is fetching 40
percent of the nation's income, emphasizing the need for expanding
cultivation of profitable, major foreign exchange-earning crops
such as paddy, beans, cotton and sugarcane as well as edible oil
crops.
</P>
<P>
He also called for turning the remaining virgin and fallow land
 on the western sector of the Ayeyawaddy River, which is the major
 area for producing paddy, into farmland.
</P>
<P>
He further called for transformation of ideas, concepts and
techniques for increasing the output of major crops.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's paddy output in the
1995-96 fiscal year was recorded at 19 million tons, while its
rice export was at 353,100 tons.
</P>
<P>
The annual growth rate of Myanmar's agriculture in the last
four fiscal years from 1992-93 to 1995-96 stood at 8.8 percent and
is targeted at 5.4 percent in the next five fiscal years from
1996-97 to 2000-01. 
</P>
</TEXT>
