<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Australia Sign Cooperation Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and Australia signed an
agreement for an Australia-Indonesia development area (AIDA)
cooperation scheme Thursday in Ambon, capital of Maluke province,
reports reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
AIDA is a sub-regional economic zone linking northern Australia
with eastern Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
AIDA's main aim is to provide the private sector with a good
business climate.
</P>
<P>
The AIDA economic and trade cooperation scheme was made because
the Australian government believed Indonesia with its economic
growth now recorded at 7.5 percent a year would become a strong
country in the years to come, the reports quoted officials here as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Australia views the sub-regional cooperation agreement as
being mutually beneficial for the two countries," Indonesia's
Coordinating Minister for Production and Distribution Hartarto
said after the signing of the accord.
</P>
<P>
"We can encourage our entrepreneurs to create joint venture
cooperation with their Australian counterparts to develop economic
growth through tourism, agriculture, education and culture,
mining, industries, trade and transportation," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto pledged to give AIDA equal status as other
sub-regional economic zones it was involved in through the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) like the
Indonesia-Malaysia-Singapore growth triangle and
Indonesia-Malaysia-Thailand growth triangle.
</P>
<P>
Australia's Minister of Foreign Affairs Alexander Downer said
on the occasion that AIDA would enhance Australian firms'
profitability, create more jobs for Australians and benefit firms
and people in eastern Indonesia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
