<HEADLINE> Thai Fruit Exports Face Tough Measures from EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Union is getting
tough with Thai plant imports found with pests and chemicals and
Thai farmers and fruit exporters are urged to take measures to
tackle the problem seriously.
</P>
<P>
The problem will escalate and Thai farmers and exporters will
be hurt if no solution is brought in, warned Thai Deputy
Agriculture Minister Krit Kongpetch Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand last year should have exported about 12-million-dollar
worth of orchid to the EU, but the actual export value was at 7.8
million dollars because many orchid exports were found without
pest-free certificates, local newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
France last year destroyed some Thai orchids found with pests
and sent officials to Thailand to solve the problem, the
newspapers quoted Thai agriculture officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Italy also seized and destroyed 4,000 tons of Thai orchids
found with pests during march 21-31 and is requiring Thailand, the
largest exporter of orchids to it, to solve the pest problem by
May, the papers said.
</P>
<P>
Krit urged Thai farmers and fruit exporters to cooperate in
overcoming the pest problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
