<HEADLINE> Italy to Help Albania Restore Judiciary System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Italy is ready to help chaos-torn
Albania rebuild its judiciary and penitentiary system as well as
train Albanian policemen and magistrates.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here today by Italian Justice Minister
Giovanni Maria Flick, following the conclusion of a two-day
Italian-Albanian justice ministers' meeting.
</P>
<P>
Flick told reporters he would visit Albania when necessary to
get first hand knowledge about how to help the country.
</P>
<P>
Italy was also ready to start training a contingent of Albanian
policemen who would act as penitentiary guards, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Council of Magistrates, the self-ruling body of
Italy's independent judiciary, would help train Albanian
magistrates, he added.
</P>
<P>
Calling the Italian aid "indispensable", Albanian Justice
Minister Spartak Ngjela said of his country: "The state has
stopped working, the justice system has been destroyed physically
and institutionally."
</P>
<P>
There was only one court working in the Albanian capital, and
two or three in the other major cities, Ngjela added.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of bilateral extradition treaty, Ngjela said
Albania would ratify the European convention on extradition.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question about the Easter weekend tragedy in
which up to 89 Albanian refugees died when their small boat
capsized after colliding with an Italian Navy corvette on the
lower Adriatic, Ngjela said: "It was an accident, not a political
issue."
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the Italian authorities for the recovery of the
sunken boat and the bodies of the victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
