<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebels Agree to Continue with Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) have agreed to continue
implementing their interim ceasefire to prevent a showdown between
soldiers and rebels that would undermine the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached this consensus after holding the third
round of low-level talks on April 23-24 at a university in the
southern Mindanao, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF signed an interim truce after a
series of military clashes in February this year. However, the
agreement was often violated with both sides blaming each other
for provoking first.
</P>
<P>
As agreed upon in the latest talks, the two sides will continue
with this truce and will further discuss at the next meeting a
broader ceasefire to cover the whole area of Mindanao where
thousands of military troops and rebels are facing a standoff.
</P>
<P>
Ghazali Gaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, said
that unless both sides can forge the comprehensive ceasefire
agreement, the formal negotiations can not take off.
</P>
<P>
Gaafar said the MILF insisted that a four-point proposal it
raised earlier should be discussed in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The proposal includes the military's adherence to the Article
of War of the Geneva Convention, a halt to army deployment in
Mindanao, recognition of MILF territories and the immediate
pull-out of troops from the conflicting area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
