<HEADLINE> U.S. Criticized for Absence From Drugs Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Colombian General
Attorney Alfonso Valdivieso today criticized the United States for
its absence from the meeting of an international drugs forum.
</P>
<P>
Valdivieso said that since the United States was one of the
countries with the largest number of drug users, there was no
reason for it to be absent.
</P>
<P>
Valdivieso chairs the International Forum of Anti-Drug
Experts which is holding a conference in Cartagena, Colombia.
</P>
<P>
He said Washington's absence left many questions unanswered,
and all those attending the meeting, including Colombia, needed an
explanation from Washington.
</P>
<P>
He demanded the U.S. government acknowledge the efforts of the
drug-producing countries in fighting drug trafficking, and their
policies to eradicate illicit drug plants.
</P>
<P>
He also demanded from the U.S. government a clear commitment to
reducing drug consumption.
</P>
<P>
Drug experts from 20 countries are gathering in Cartagena for a
joint analysis of the mechanisms to reduce the demand and supply
of drugs at an international level.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day meeting sponsored by Colombia's Foreign
Ministry, the experts are also expected to prepare a document to
be presented at the United Nations General Assembly in 1998.
</P>
