<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (43-44) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (43-44)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What is the relationship between the judiciary of the
Hong Kong SAR and its counterparts in other local districts of the
interior area?
</P>
<P>
Answer: According to the Basic Law, no departments of the
central government and no province, autonomous region and
centrally-administered municipality may interfere in affairs to
be administered by the Hong Kong SAR on its own in accordance with
the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong SAR may, through consultations and in accordance
with law, maintain judicial relations with judicial organs of
other parts of the country, and they may render mutual assistance,
the Basic Law says.
</P>
<P>
It is clear that the Supreme People's Court, the Supreme
People's Procuratorate and judicial organs of provinces,
autonomous regions and centrally-administered municipalities
cannot extend their judicial power to the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Criminal cases that occur in the Hong Kong SAR are subject to
the power of judicial organs of the Hong Kong SAR only. Similarly,
the judicial power of courts in the Hong Kong SAR cannot reach the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
Question: What is the relationship between the judiciary of the
Hong Kong SAR and its executive and legislative branches?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Judiciary independence is an important principle for
the juridical operation of the Hong Kong SAR. Judicial organs of
the Hong Kong SAR are independent of the SAR's executive and
legislative branches and will try cases independently, free from
any interference from any individuals and groups so as to achieve
judicial fairness. Members of the judiciary are immune from legal
action in the performance of their judicial duties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
