<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Faces No Immediate Major Financial Danger: IMF Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The chief of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) asserted today that he sees no immediate
danger of a financial crisis like that shock to international
markets in Mexico in later 1994.
</P>
<P>
Michel Camdessus, the Managing Director of the 181-nation IMF
made the remarks while addressing a press briefing here prior to
the joint spring meetings of the IMF and World Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said, "such crises are widely unpredictable," the IMF would
pay closer attention "to hot spots on the planet" so it doesn't
get caught by surprise again.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said he sees no reason for alarm in Japan, where the
fund has maintained close contact with Japanese officials on
"putting their financial sector in order." Camdessus also said
South Korea, Thailand and Brazil do not face threatening financial
situations.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus has said the world's next financial problem will be a
banking crisis or will have a banking system weakness as a major
component.
</P>
<P>
On other topics, he welcomed the U.S. Federal Reserve Board's
March 25 decision to raise interest rates. It will send a prudent
signal to global financial markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief today also issued a statement applauding debt
relief package for Uganda. "I am certain that this will be an
extremely positive signal to the rest of the world, and I was
happy to hear that the Ugandan Minister of Planning and Economic
Development immediately reacted to this decision by warmly
welcoming this package of debt relief."
</P>
<P>
Under the package, Uganda is expected to receive about 340
million (in Net Present Value(NPV) terms or in April 1998 dollars)
from all its creditors, which represents a reduction of about 20
percent in Uganda's debt. The IMF share of this initiative is
about 70 million dollars. All multilateral creditors are expected
to reduce their claims on Uganda in NPV terms by about 20 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
