<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Begins Title Defence with Easy Wins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The all-mighty
Chinese women's squad kicked off their title defence with two easy
matches at the 44th World Table Tennis Championships which opened
here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team, which has won the Corbillion Cup for the
women's team event for 11 times, blanked Australia and Russia in
Group A competitions.
</P>
<P>
With world No. 1 Deng Yaping benched, Chinese youngsters Yang
Ying, Li Ju and Wang Nan won their opening matches against the
Australian team.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Deng, who has won a grand slam of the Olympic,
world championship and World Cup titles, returned to the court
later Thursday, contributing one point to China's 3-0 victory over
Russia.
</P>
<P>
China's best defensive player Ding Song suffered a surprising
loss to less known Robert Smrekar as the defending champion team
overcame Slovenia 3-1 at their opening men's team match.
</P>
<P>
Smrekar, rated 115th in the world, clinched a 12-21, 21-12,
21-15 victory over world No. 7 player after China's Olympic
champion Liu Guoliang won the first game.
</P>
<P>
Ding looked compeletly out of form as he failed to put up his
trademark chop-and-attack game.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old Chinese jumped to international stardom in the
1995 world championships, where he snatched a crucial point in
China's 3-2 final victory over three-time world champion Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Ding also ousted 1991 world singles champion Jorgen Persson of
Sweden and then world No. 1 Jean-Michael Saive of Beigium en route
to finishing fourth in the last Worlds.
</P>
<P>
"Ding Song is no longer a secret to Europeans," said Chinese
head coach Cai Zhenhua. "They have been studying his style since
the 1995 championships."
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 Kong Linghui and Olympic champion Liu Guoliang won
the last two rubbers for China.
</P>
<P>
In the most dramatic match of the day, Jean-Philippe Saive
saved Belgium by winning two games while his elder brother
Jean-Michael lost as many in the match against Belarus.
</P>
<P>
Philippe, ranked 50th in the world, upset world No. 4 Vladimir
Samsonov and blanked Evgueni Chtchetinine to help Belgium win 3-2.
</P>
<P>
World No. 8 Michael Saive, singles runner-up in the 1993
Worlds, was stunned 2-1 by Chtchetinine in the opening game.
Saive was so angry with his poor performance that he threw his bat
to the ground after the match.
</P>
<P>
Philippe Saive evened the score as he overcome one-set deficit
to beat Samsonov 13-21, 21-12, 21-19. The 20-year-old Samsonov, a
player willing to rally until his rival leaves an opening, found
Philippe's forehand topspins too strong to return.
</P>
<P>
Andras Podpinka put Belgium ahead with a 21-12, 21-10 victory
over Pavel Chomtchonak.
</P>
<P>
Michael Saive continued his poor form in the fourth game, lost
in straight sets to Samsonov.
</P>
<P>
Philippe saved face for the Saives as he snatched the deciding
set over Chtchetinine 21-17, 21-15.
</P>
<P>
"Philippe is a hero for the Belgium team," said Belgian head
coach Wang Dayong.
</P>
<P>
"His elder brother played poorly today, but Michael always
comes into shape late," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sweden rested world No. 2 Jan-Ove Waldner and No.15 Peter
Karlsson on Thursday as Jorgen Persson led Thomas Von Scheele and
Kayode Kadiri to beat Slovakia 3-1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
