<HEADLINE> Greece Agrees to Help Dispatch Romanian Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Greece today accepted the request
put forward by Romania in assisting the latter to dispatch its
troops to be stationed in southern Albania.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Undersecretary Yiannos Kranidiotis said at press
conference that the Romanian troops participating in the
Italian-led multinational security force in Albania would arrive
in Greece by ship and be transported to Albania by Greek vehicles.
</P>
<P>
"It is a development with considerable political significance,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations approved the formation of a 5,000
multinational security force last month to oversee the
distribution of humanitarian aid to Albania.
</P>
<P>
Troops from eight countries such as Greece and Romania are
expected to implement the U.N.-mandated relief operations which
will last three months. 
</P>
