<HEADLINE> China Stresses Peaceful Settlement of Mideast Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government had
all along stood for the settlement of the question of Jerusalem
through peaceful negotiations by the parties concerned on the
basis of the relevant UN resolutions, Chinese Ambassador Qin
Huasun said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 10th Emergency Special Session of the UN
General Assembly this afternoon, Qin said the construction of
Jewish settlements in East Jerusalem had brought the Middle East
peace process to another deadlock and tensions in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We express grave concern over this development and once again
urge the Israeli government to immediately stop building Jewish
settlement in East Jerusalem," he said.
</P>
<P>
In order to move out of the current difficulties and prevent
the whole Middle East peace process from going backwards, all
parties concerned must make efforts to remove obstruction and
obstacles and implement all the agreements reached as soon as
possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called the parties concerned to exercise restraint and keep
calm, cherish the hard-won peace situation and strictly observe
the agreements reached by Palestine and Israel so as to create
conditions for an early, fair, reasonable and lasting solution to
the Middle East question.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Emergency Special Session of the General Assembly
focuses on discussion of illegal Israeli actions in occupied East
Jerusalem and the rest of the occupied Palestinian territory. It
is held, at the request of the Group of Arab States and state
members of the Non-Aligned Movement, under the 1950 General
Assembly resolution 377 (V), entitled "Uniting for peace."
</P>
<P>
The UN Security Council held twice extensive discussions on
illegal Israeli actions and failed to adopt a resolution because
of U.S. vetos on March 7 and 21. Under such circumstances, the
General Assembly shall continue the matter with a view to making
appropriate recommendations to the members for collective
measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
