<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fraud Costs EU 40 Billion Pounds Each Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- International fraud costs the
European Union (EU) more than 40 billion pounds (about 65 billion
U.S. dollars) a year largely because regulatory discrepancies
between EU countries are exploited by professional criminals,
according to a recent report.
</P>
<P>
The report, produced for the EU Commission by forensic
accountants at Deloitte and Touche, highlighted the increasing
sophistication of fraudsters by saying that there is now an
escalating technological "arms race" between criminals and their
victims.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed that fraud within EU is of such a scale
that it has the power seriously to distort competition between
member states and can touch most individuals in the 15-nation
bloc.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone pays for fraud through higher taxes, higher prices
and shoddy goods, even if they are not direct victims," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Will Inglis, one of the authors of the report, was quoted by
press reports as saying: "There is a trend for organized criminals
to devote more effort to white-collar crime, because the risks are
lower and the rewards are higher."
</P>
<P>
The whole question of crime and fraud within Europe is expected
to be debated at the concluding session of the EU
Inter-Governmental Conference in Amsterdam in mid-June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
