<DOCNO> XIE19970425.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP to Hold Conference to Encourage Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program will hold a round-table conference here next week to
promote private investments and free trade in Africa, according to
a UNDP press release today.
</P>
<P>
During the conference from April 29 to 30, delegates from all
16 member states of OHADA (French acronym for Organization for the
Harmonization of Business Law in Africa) will meet potential
donors to put forward their plan to have the business law of the
members states coordinated.
</P>
<P>
The initiative comes after three years of steady economic
growth in the OHADA area, from around two percent in 1994 to four
percent in 1995 and five percent in 1996. Growth has been due
mostly to the renewed dynamism of crash crop exports such as
cotton seed, coffee, cocoa and groundnuts; tourism; forestry; and
mining output like oil, gold, diamonds, uranium, bauxite and
phosphates.
</P>
<P>
In order to reinforce the positive economic trends, OHADA
countries need to attract private investment. OHADA's total
financing requirements come to 50 million U.S. dollars over a
period of 12 years. Half the sum will come from member states. The
other half will be sought from donors.
</P>
<P>
OHADA's main objective is therefore to ensure legal and
judicial security for foreign and national private investors
operating in the member countries. To achieve this, it relies on
three mechanisms:
</P>
<P>
- Introduction of uniform modern law for all member states;
</P>
<P>
- Establishment of a common, independent judicial institution
responsible for settling business disputes effectively, rapidly
and transparently;
</P>
<P>
- Establishment of a school of magistrature responsible for
providing advanced training to magistrates and legal staff.
</P>
<P>
According to UNDP, the potential for private investment in
Africa is growing due to the strict policies of structural
adjustment which are being enacted, including the privatization of
public enterprise.
</P>
<P>
"OHADA is a concrete measure designed to address this problem
and should be encouraged," says Alan Doss, acting Director of
UNDP's Regional Bureau for Africa. "UNDP lends full support to the
OHADA program which falls in line with our agency's main objective
to reduce global poverty. Creating a dynamic business environment
in Africa is an important initial step towards improving the life
conditions of millions of people in one of the world's poorest
regions."
</P>
<P>
OHADA members are Benin, Burkina Faso, Cameroon, the Central
African Republic, Comoros, Congo, Cote d'Ivoire, Gabon, Guinea,
Guinea Bissau, Equatorial Guinea, Mali, Niger, Senegal, Chad,
Togo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
