<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek PM Calls for More Say for Smaller States in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Greek Prime Minister
Constantinos Simitis today called for more say for smaller
countries during the process of the European Union (EU) reform.
</P>
<P>
Simitis, who is on a six-day visit to Germany, met German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl today in Bonn with discussions focusing on
the EU's ongoing reform conference known as the Inter-Governmental
Conference (IGC).
</P>
<P>
One of the major issues on the IGC agenda is to consider
streamlining the way of decision-making by the 15-member EU in
order to prepare it, among other things, for taking in new members
from Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Bonn has been backing an expansion of majority voting instead
of the current system which gives each member the right of veto.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said that while his government supported more use of
majority voting, it also wanted to maintain the right of veto for
issues which would effect vital national interests.
</P>
<P>
He also demanded that the same membership requirements apply to
all EU countries when the EU makes the decision in May 1998 on
which countries will be able to qualify for the planned single
European currency, the Euro, on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Simitis admitted that his country would not be able to make the
first wave to join the Euro in 1999, but is prepared to join the
club in the year 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
