<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Appear Likely to Approve Chemical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate would most
likely approve the Chemical Weapons Convention during a vote
scheduled later today as a leading Republican opponent changes his
position to support the pact.
</P>
<P>
Trent Lott, the Senate Majority Leader, said he would vote for
the treaty after President Bill Clinton promised the Senate that
he would withdraw from the Chemical Weapons Treaty (CWC) if the
the pact inadvertently results in the spread of of chemical
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the promise in a letter to Lott, which is part of
a campaign launched by the administration for the ratification of
the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Lott told a news conference, "This commitment is
unprecedented," adding that the assurances had affected his
thinking although he still remained uncommitted on how to vote for
the pact.
</P>
<P>
Lott and Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, have been lobbying for not approving the treaty,
demanding amendments to the document.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is expected to vote later today on the convention,
which is to take effect on April 29 with or without the U.S.'s
participation. A two-thirds majority would be needed for approval.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Clinton said he was "prepared to withdraw from
the treaty" if other countries used its provisions to proliferate
chemical weapons technology and endanger U.S. security.
</P>
<P>
Article 10 and 11 of the treaty require contracting parties to
provide chemical weapons defenses and call for exchanges of
peaceful chemicals and technology among the parties.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's letter aims at easing the concerns of the opponents
about the provisions. Lott and Helms insist that some countries
may use the provisions to spread poison gas and attack the U.S.
chemical weapons technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
