<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Medicare Feared Bankrupt in 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Medicare trustees say the
nation's hospital insurance trust fund can last only four years.
</P>
<P>
The latest projected lifespan of the system represents a
negligible change from last year's forecast.
</P>
<P>
Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala said,
"Today's report makes clear that the time to act to preserve
Medicare is now. With insolvency only four years away, the
administration and the Congress have no time to waste."
</P>
<P>
Without immediate legislation, the government-funded health
insurance program will be unable to pay for hospital services,
hospices and home health agencies for millions of people.
</P>
<P>
Budget negotiations between the White House and Congress are
stuck partly because of differing views by Democrats and
Republicans on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Democrats contended the Republican was seeking to
slash Medicare spending for the elderly at least in part to
provide some money for tax cuts aimed at the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
Republicans argued they were trying to craft reforms, based on
the health program for federal employees, that offers seniors
broad choices of health care plans to foster competition that
could keep health costs down.
</P>
<P>
In a current budget proposal, President Bill Clinton has
offered Medicare savings provisions totaling some 100 billion
dollars over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Shalala said these savings would increase the life expectancy
of Medicare until 2008, but she was urging a bipartisan commission
to find a longer-term solution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
